<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 10 日星期四 09:32:48 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Never Tweet]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>特朗普的扩音器又回来困扰他了。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/hlQelfIbUlM0junmRSxbP9YxrJY=/0x0:4162x2341/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/GettyImages_869760894/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普讲话" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>曼德尔·颜/法新社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>还记得唐纳德·特朗普发推文吗？当然可以！这位第 45 任总统一次以 280 个字符的帖子吸引了全世界的关注，直到两年半前他被停职。他利用这个平台进行恶搞、骚扰和撒谎。他放大了阴谋论者和他们的观点。他与不稳定的核世界大国对抗，并向否认选举的人讲述了 1 月 6 日在国家广场举行的抗议活动：“去那里，会很疯狂！”这正是我们公众所能看到的。<br><br>今天早些时候，一份未密封的法庭意见显示，为特别检察官杰克·史密斯工作的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/09/us/politics/trump-twitter-account-search-warrant.html">检察官</a>在一月份获得了搜查令，可以访问 @realDonaldTrump 目前处于休眠状态的帐户，也许是为了了解幕后发生了什么（如果有的话）——用户看不到的消息或草稿。根据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://static.foxnews.com/foxnews.com/content/uploads/2023/08/gov.uscourts.cadc_.39513.1208541751.0.pdf">意见</a>，搜查令“指示推特提供”与特朗普账户相关的数据和记录。该公司最初拒绝遵守，因为搜查令中包含一项条款，禁止 Twitter 通知特朗普政府已发布搜查令。在被藐视法庭并被罚款 35 万美元后，Twitter 最终交出了这些信息。<br><br>据我采访过的专家称，搜查令看起来很简单，而且保密要素在刑事调查中很常见，检察官担心证据被销毁或处理不当。 （如果特朗普收到警告，他可能会删除史密斯希望找到的任何内容。）值得注意的是，Twitter 经常收到政府的信息请求，有时甚至会遵守政府的信息请求。 <em>Rest of World</em> 4 月份的一份报告<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://restofworld.org/2023/elon-musk-twitter-government-orders/">显示</a>，在埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 的领导下，该公司“收到了 971 项政府要求，并完全遵守了其中 808 项要求”。当然，特朗普的推特账户不是普通的推特账户，对这位前总统的指控——涉及处理机密材料以及涉嫌试图阻挠权力和平移交——都是非同寻常的。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/">阅读：为什么埃隆杀死了那只鸟</a><br><br>加州大学伯克利分校法学教授奥林·科尔 (Orin Kerr) 告诉我：“通过在线账户寻找阴谋证据是很常见的。” “如果你抛开这种令人震惊的事实，这种情况发生在一位前总统身上，这是有道理的。他们正在调查一起犯罪行为，而他肯定经常使用推特。”<br><br>史密斯的逮捕令引发了各种各样的问题，比如特别检察官可能在寻找什么，以及检察官在访问前总统的账户时可能会看到什么。<br><br>调查人员会梳理特朗普的直接信息吗？是否可以从与 @realDonaldTrump 关联的 IP 地址中收集有用的信息？检察官可能还想确定发送某些推文的具体设备，以便将它们与特朗普更紧密地联系起来：特朗普在 2019 年<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/16/trump-scavino-1327921">告诉</a><em>Politico</em> ，虽然他“通常”自己写推文，但他的助手丹·斯卡维诺有时会提供帮助。<br><br> “最终，我们只是不知道史密斯得到了什么，”科尔说。 “有一些暗示认为他们正在进行关键词搜索，这可能意味着检察官无法访问所有内容，但我们只是不知道。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trump-indictment-gop-jan-6/674895/">阅读：特朗普对民主的威胁现在是系统性的</a><br><br>当然，人们对世界上最多产、最重要的推特用户之一如何在幕后使用该应用程序感到好奇。理论上，特朗普未发送的推文草稿可以用作证据，尽管我们根本不知道史密斯是否拥有它们。唐纳德·特朗普以避开包括电子邮件在内的大多数形式的数字通信而闻名，并且<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2023/01/trump-has-reportedly-discovered-the-modern-magic-of-texting.html">最近才</a>开始发短信，他是否直接向人们发送消息？如果不是，他的直接消息收件箱可能不太有趣；特朗普恢复的账户在该平台上只有51名关注者，其中大多数是官方账户和家庭成员，并且已经关闭了私信，这意味着除非总统回复他们，否则外界无法发起联系。<br><br>正如克尔指出的那样，不能保证挖掘特朗普臭名昭著的账户会产生任何实质性的东西：“如果没有直接消息，那里可能没有很多证据。”检察官完全有可能只是获得了搜查令，帮助将特朗普的推文作为法庭上的证据：如果问题被提出来，建立一个官方的监管链将消除对任何特定推文是否实际存在的怀疑。<br><br>关于特朗普推特账户的搜索，有很多我们不知道、也可能永远不会知道的事情。如果你知道我不是一名律师，你不会感到惊讶，而只是一名沉迷于 Twitter 的科技作家，已经报道该平台十多年了。但我相信，任何人都应该从今天的新闻中吸取一个无可争议的教训：永远不要发推文。 （特别是如果你认为自己有可能最终陷入联邦检察官指控你密谋欺骗政府的情况的话。）如果特别检察官发现特朗普账户中埋藏着确凿无疑的证据，那么公众将面临更大的风险。挖掘工作将是特朗普十多年来的数字夸夸其谈的直接结果。他对这个平台的痴迷导致了这一刻。它标志着特朗普推特账户的演变，从好奇心变成武器，最后变成合法目标。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 22:40:03 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/trump-twitter-account-special-counsel-search-warrant/674969/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/trump-twitter-account-special-counsel-search-warrant/674969/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Sports Betting Won]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>当然，ESPN 正在转向赌博。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/bQiIIhPoG0EYzmV4BNDkQTR3TrM=/0x0:960x540/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/sports_bets_sm_2/original.gif" alt="ESPN 徽标，上方带有老虎机图标" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔安妮·因佩里奥/大西洋月刊。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>世界上不存在所谓<em>明智的</em>体育投注，但无论以何种标准衡量，我所做的第一个投注都特别愚蠢。那是 2022 年 1 月下旬，几周前移动游戏应用程序在纽约才变得合法。我成功地忽略了所有这些，直到我看到辛辛那提猛虎队的四分卫乔·伯罗穿着夏尔巴外套、黑色高领毛衣、巨大的金链子和无框太阳镜走进堪萨斯城的箭头体育场观看亚足联冠军赛。我心想，<em>那个人今天不会输掉一场足球比赛</em>。<br><br>当我看到伯罗的服装时，我立即知道该怎么做，尽管我以前从未真正考虑过体育博彩。注册一个新的 DraftKings 账户让我获得了 100 美元的免费投注，我把它押在孟加拉虎队的输赢盘上。一旦游戏应用程序的使用合法化，其广告几乎覆盖了城市的每个角落。在其他几十个已将移动体育博彩合法化的州中，情况也大致如此，在<em>无法</em>进行赌博的地方，赌博甚至是不可避免的：对投注赔率和分差的坦率讨论已成为体育的一大特色媒体，这个话题长期以来一直被禁止。<br><br>体育博彩热潮几乎没有放缓的迹象。昨天下午，ESPN发布了一项既史无前例又令人期待的消息。今年秋天，在与游戏公司 Penn Entertainment 达成的​​为期 10 年、价值 20 亿美元的协议中，美国最具实力的体育媒体公司将推出自己的数字体育博彩 ESPN Bet。此次合作将带领 ESPN 及其人才在其电视网络、网站和智能手机应用程序上推广体育博彩，巩固五年前似乎几乎不可能的转型。博彩一度被完全排除在主流体育运动之外，但现在却与几乎各个层面的业务密不可分。博彩公司赞助电视报道、<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.caesarssuperdome.com/">在体育场上刻上自己的名字</a>、在体育场内经营体育博彩并与球队合作。游戏结束了。赌赢了。<br><br>在现代职业体育史上的大部分时间里，即使是最含糊地承认一些观众可能出于纯粹的热爱之外的原因对比赛感兴趣，在很大程度上也是被禁止的。几十年来，美国国家橄榄球联盟甚至禁止转播其比赛的网络讨论分差。随着幻想体育在 2000 年代流行起来，该公约慢慢开始受到侵蚀，但真正的转折点出现在 2018 年，当时最高法院的一项裁决为各州体育博彩合法化扫清了道路。五年后，经过一场激烈的游戏行业<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/11/20/business/sports-betting-lobbying-kansas.html">游说</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/11/20/business/sports-betting-lobbying-kansas.html">活动</a>，36 个州和华盛顿特区也加入了内华达州的行列。其中最具颠覆性的是现在允许在移动应用程序中进行投注，将体育博彩带入美国人的口袋。<br><br>只要有一点点技巧，博彩业就是一项利润极高的事业。总的来说，人们很不擅长赌博。突然之间，数以百万计可能从未去过赌场的新投注者可以在体育酒吧或沙发上用手机进行即兴投注，包括对现场比赛中的即时细节进行投注，例如下一场比赛的结果打球或击球。 DraftKings 和 FanDuel 等公司已经拥有强大的应用程序和大量玩幻想体育的现有用户，它们是最先利用游戏淘金热的公司，以及凯撒和米高梅等知名赌场运营商。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2022/09/14/as-more-states-legalize-the-practice-19-of-u-s-adults-say-they-have-bet-money-on-sports-in-the-past-year/">皮尤研究中心 2022 年的一项调查</a>发现，近五分之一的美国人在前一年参与过体育博彩——考虑到美国一些人口最多的州，包括加利福尼亚州和德克萨斯州，迄今为止一直抵制合法化，这一比例在人口中占很大比例。<br><br>即使对于那些对此不感兴趣的普通球迷来说，赌博也已成为不可避免的事情——应用程序广告在比赛转播期间无处不在，游戏术语是体育解说员词典的标准组成部分，而球员和教练现在经常因为自己的赌博而陷入非常引人注目的麻烦。的利用。一旦合法化开始，一些不太传统的体育媒体机构很快就与游戏公司合作，将读者引导到现有的服务或开设自己的服务。现在，即使是强大的广播网络也比以往任何时候都没有动力坚持在这个话题上的强硬立场。他们可以辩称观众的需求已经改变，而未能进入博彩业务实际上会对观众造成伤害。 ESPN 主席吉米·皮塔罗 (Jimmy Pitaro) 去年在接受<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theathletic.com/4759827/2023/08/08/espn-bet-penn-sportsbook/"><em>The Athletic</em></a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theathletic.com/4759827/2023/08/08/espn-bet-penn-sportsbook/">采访</a>时谈到了博彩报道和合作伙伴关系：“这是我们的球迷对我们的期望，”他说。 “所以它不是‘拥有就好’，在这一点上它几乎是必须具备的。”<br><br>不管需求如何，所有的游戏现金都让广播公司陷入了特别疲软的时刻。尽管 ESPN <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/02/business/media/espn-disney.html">仍然利润丰厚</a>——每年可达数十亿美元——但有线电视的衰落使得持续增长看起来很困难，而增长正是股东所希望的。无论你如何创造性地计算，流媒体订阅都不太可能弥补这一差距。媒体高管会去有钱的地方，而现在，最大的新资金都流向了那些鼓励观众赌博的人。如果连 ESPN 都坚持不了，而且显然没有尝试的欲望，那么就没有人能坚持了。<br><br>这些大笔资金并不能保证拯救企业，甚至不能保证持续很长时间。长达数年的奢华营销和促销活动填补了体育媒体的口袋，旨在吸引新市场中的新投注者，而其巨额费用意味着许多移动投注应用程序尚未盈利。体育博彩赚钱的压力<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fox-to-wind-down-sports-betting-site-fox-bet-f9fda8d2">已经开始增加</a>，并且它已经扼杀了 Fox Bet，这是与 ESPN 计划今年秋天推出的最接近的现有类似平台。<br><br>但在进入这个市场时，ESPN 比其任何假定的竞争对手都拥有更多的优势，并且存在更多的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.espn.com/espn/columns/story?columnist=schreiber_leanne&amp;id=2866241">利益冲突</a>。 ESPN 拥有美国几乎所有主要体育赛事的部分或全部转播权，这意味着它对整个业务的运作方式具有巨大的影响力。它也是美国最大的体育新闻来源，ESPN 对这个行业的报道方式已经影响到独立体育博彩公司如何设定赔率以及普通人如何下注。现在，ESPN 将掌控所有三个方面：影响联盟、告知公众以及设定赌注。 （ESPN 表示，它将在记者和博彩业务之间保持<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://frontofficesports.com/moving-the-lines-how-will-espn-insiders-play-into-espn-bet/">严格的界限</a>。）<br><br>如果你是（很多很多）球迷中的一员，你觉得现在通过对博彩玩家意味着什么来过滤你的大部分体育新闻感到恼火，那么随着 ESPN 更加集中地参与游戏，情况只会变得更糟。或者，也许它只会让你变成一个违背你更好判断的赌徒，正如预期的那样。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/espn-sports-betting-mobile-gambling/674967/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/espn-sports-betting-mobile-gambling/674967/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Republicans’ Failed Gamble in Ohio]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Russell Berman 谈昨天的结果如何给民主党带来 2024 年的希望<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/CJRF3O-D1bbFW-jI9JLrTDxGCeE=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/ohio/original.jpg" alt="标有“俄亥俄州已投票”的贴纸" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>马德琳·霍丁斯基 / 纽约时报 / Redux</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>昨天，俄亥俄州选民拒绝了一项提高州宪法修改门槛的投票措施。尽管第一期提案并未明确涉及堕胎，但较高的门槛可能会成为阻止 11 月堕胎权倡议获得通过的一种方式。我与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-special-election-issue-1-abortion/674957/">一直报道</a>俄亥俄州故事的拉塞尔·伯曼 (Russell Berman) 进行了交谈，了解了这一结果对生殖权利支持者以及 2024 年选举的意义。<br><br>首先，这是来自<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的三个新故事：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/rural-montana-housing-crisis-supply/674950/">反加州</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/qin-gang-china-missing-foreign-minister/674954/">为什么你应该担心中国失踪的部长</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/foomscrolling-ai-chatgpt-lk-99-superconductor/674955/">欢迎来到“foomscrolling”时代。</a></li><strong>关于时机的一切</strong><br><br><b>洛拉·凯利：</b>这次特别选举的结果让您感到惊讶的话，是什么？<br><br> <b>Russell Berman：</b>这次选举的结果实际上并不令人意外。民主党在俄亥俄州的民意调查中长期连败，但堕胎权却在民意调查中取得了连胜。去年，在每一个有堕胎权相关修正案的州，堕胎权一方都获胜。这种情况在佛蒙特州和加利福尼亚州等蓝州以及堪萨斯州和肯塔基州等红州都发生过。<br><br>回想起来，在俄亥俄州，共和党人甚至将这一点列入选票的事实令人惊讶，因为他们知道其他地方，尤其是堪萨斯州发生了什么。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2022/08/kansas-abortion-vote/671029/">一年前，在堪萨斯州</a>，堕胎权一方以比俄亥俄州更大的优势击败了一项反堕胎投票法案。这在当时来说，是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2022/08/kansas-abortion-vote-midterms/671046/">一个很大的惊喜</a>。但现在，看到堕胎问题对于动员堕胎权支持者有多么强大，昨晚在俄亥俄州发生的事情并不令人意外。<br><br><b>劳拉：</b>在<i>多布斯</i>做出决定一年多后，这一结果告诉我们选民对堕胎的热情如何？<br><br><b>拉塞尔：</b>它非常清楚地告诉我们，围绕堕胎权仍有很多精力。这给民主党人进入 2024 年带来了更多希望。这次选举表明，民主党人仍然可以依靠堕胎作为一个问题，特别是在堕胎机会和堕胎权利受到威胁的州。 2022 年，民主党候选人在红色或紫色州的表现要好得多，这些州明显感觉到选举可能会决定是否允许堕胎。<br><br>在俄亥俄州，你仍然可以看到那种能量——只要看看投票率就知道了。昨天俄亥俄州的选票上唯一的议题是第一期。没有初选；没有初选。没有候选人竞选。昨天人们去俄亥俄州投票只是为了对这项宪法修正案进行投票。投票率几乎是 2022 年 5 月全州初选的两倍。而且这是 8 月份！回到你的第一个问题，如果说这次选举有什么让我感到惊讶的话，那就不是结果，而是投票率。它确实超出了最广泛的预测。<br><br><b>洛拉：</b> <i>“堕胎”</i>这个词没有出现在俄亥俄州选票提案文本中的任何地方。选民如何得知这次特别选举与 11 月堕胎倡议有关？<br><br><b>拉塞尔：</b>这完全取决于时机。几个月来，人们一直在请愿，希望将堕胎问题纳入秋季选票。俄亥俄州的选民知道这一点。共和党主导的立法机构不断试图将第一个问题列入选票，以拦截堕胎修正案，并最终通过了一项安排在八月举行的选举的法案。<br><br>共和党人从未真正否认，这项措施至少部分地——真正地、全部地——与今年 11 月即将推出的堕胎修正案有关，尽管他们强调修改州宪法会影响其他问题。他们的信息指出，“特殊利益”资金可能会进入该州，并试图影响对大麻合法化、提高最低工资和通过枪支管制法的投票。但选民明白这实际上是关于堕胎的。这项修正案的反对者已经准备好向他们表明这一点。<br><br><b>洛拉：</b>这次选举告诉我们有关其他州堕胎权斗争的什么信息？接下来你在哪里寻找？<br><br><b>拉塞尔：</b>这肯定会继续鼓舞民主党，即堕胎权一方，他们基本上正在寻找公民主导的投票倡议可以改变宪法的任何地方，因为共和党控制着大多数州的立法机构，而且他们已经对红色州的控制非常严格，特别是在南方。<br><br>具体来说，我们正在寻找佛罗里达州和亚利桑那州。在佛罗里达州，堕胎权的支持者现在正在收集请愿书，试图将保护堕胎机会的宪法修正案纳入 2024 年的选票中。这很重要，因为立法机关和州长 Ron DeSantis 刚刚通过了一项在六周后禁止堕胎的法律。在共和党也控制立法机构的亚利桑那州，堕胎权的支持者也计划收集请愿书，将修正案提交投票。<br><br><b>有关的：</b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-special-election-issue-1-abortion/674957/">堕胎的强烈反对波及俄亥俄州</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-issue-1-special-election-abortion/674923/">下一场堕胎大斗争</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>夏威夷前所未有的野火和强风导致<a href="https://www.cnn.com/us/live-news/maui-wildfires-08-09-23/index.html">大范围疏散</a>，并造成至少六人死亡。</li><li>一份新公开的法庭文件<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/08/09/politics/special-counsel-trump-twitter-search-warrant/index.html">显示，</a>特别检察官杰克·史密斯获得了对唐纳德·特朗普推特账户的搜查令。</li><li>据估计，有 41 名试图从突尼斯前往欧洲的移民在翻船后<a href="https://www.ft.com/content/586f0b56-21d6-4b74-8e84-8342bc61fe9a">死亡</a>。</li><strong>快讯</strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/up-for-debate/"><b>有待辩论</b></a><b>：</b>尽管多纳德·特朗普采取了行动并受到起诉，但他仍然是共和党初选选民的首选。 <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/13-readers-on-what-trump-voters-want/674961/">康纳·弗里德斯多夫收集了</a>读者对原因的看法。</li> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">在这里探索我们所有的时事通讯。</a></em><br><br><strong>晚读</strong><br><br>我对触发警告的看法是错误的<br><br><em>吉尔·菲利波维奇</em><br><br><p>2008 年，当我还是女性博客的撰稿人时，评论者开始要求在讨论令人痛苦的话题（最常见的是性侵犯）的帖子顶部发出警告。不幸的是，暴力不可避免地成为女权主义写作的核心。强奸、家庭暴力、种族主义暴力、厌女症——这些事件不可磨灭地塑造着女性的生活，无论我们是直接经历这些事件，还是因害怕它们而调整自己的行为。</p><p>当时，我确信这样的警告有时是必要的，以传达当前主题的严重性（ <i>“严重问题”</i>这个词在我的署名下出现了很多次）。即便如此，我还是对添加更多触发警告的要求感到恼火，尤其是当标题已经明确了帖子的内容时。但警告正在成为在线女权主义空间的常态，帖子顶部的四个字——“触发警告：性侵犯”——似乎是为了我们社区的福祉而做出的一个简单的妥协。我们以为我们正在让世界变得更美好一点。直到很久以后我才意识到我们可能是问题的一部分。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/trigger-warnings-feminism-teen-girls-mental-health/674759/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/robotaxis-san-francisco-self-driving-car/674956/">旧金山的机器人出租车存在问题。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/gardening-beginning-principles/674962/">园艺方面别想太多。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/robert-smithson-artist-spiral-jetty/674761/">罗伯特·史密森的意外事件纪念碑</a></li><b>文化突破</b><br><br><b>读。</b>伊布拉姆·X·肯迪<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/black-folk-book-working-class-blair-lm-kelley/674935/">(Ibram X. Kendi) 写道</a>，布莱尔·LM·凯利 (Blair LM Kelley) 在她的新书《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/black-folk-the-roots-of-the-black-working-class-blair-lm-kelley/9781631496554?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>黑人民间：黑人工人阶级的根源》</i></a>中打破了<i>工人阶级</i>与<i>白人</i>同义的政治神话。<br><br><b>手表。</b>美国可能会退出女足世界杯（福克斯电视台播出），但特约撰稿人富兰克林·福尔已经找到了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-world-cup-colombia/674958/">另一个可以支持的国家</a>。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br><i>你听</i>大西洋<i>播客吗？我们很想听听您对</i>大西洋广播电台<i>或</i>操作指南<i>系列的想法。</i>请<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/listener-survey/"><i>在此处</i></a><i>向我们发送您的反馈</i><i>。</i><br><br> <i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br><em>当您使用本新闻通讯中的链接购买书籍时，我们会收到佣金。感谢您对大西洋月刊的支持</em><em>。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/ohio-special-election-issue-1-abortion/674966/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/ohio-special-election-issue-1-abortion/674966/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[13 Readers on What Trump Voters Want]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> “真正重要的是候选人是否赋予选民身份，”一位读者辩称。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Ood16RFziklBTZ74MXa-uC-fVQQ=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/trump_supporters/original.jpg" alt="一名成年男子在特朗普集会上抱着一个孩子。两人都戴着红色帽子。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>达蒙·温特 / 纽约时报 / Redux</figcaption></figure><i data-stringify-type="italic">欢迎来到辩论。康纳·弗里德斯多夫每周都会收集及时的对话，并征求读者对一个发人深省的问题的回答。随后，他发表了一些深思熟虑的回复。</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/up-for-debate" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/up-for-debate" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册时事通讯。</a></i><br><br>上周，我向读者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/a-progressive-city-debates-crime/674909/">提出了这个问题</a>：“唐纳德·特朗普犯下了可悲的罪行，被指控多项罪行，但他仍然是共和党总统初选中最受选民欢迎的候选人。为什么你认为他仍然是他们的第一选择？”<br><br><em>为了长度和清晰度，回复已被编辑。</em><br><br>兰德尔·R. (Randall R.) 认为特朗普的支持者真诚地渴望国家伟大：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">许多人支持特朗普的原因（如果你有礼貌地听听他们的话）是因为他们想让美国再次伟大，而在显赫地位和实现他们所说的目标的明显能力方面，没有其他人能与特朗普相媲美。面对当前存在的内部冲突，美国伟大的最有前途和最重要的部分。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">这是政客传播的一种幻觉，提供一种令人上瘾的快感，使人们与现实的某些部分脱节。它并不能让美国变得伟大。但让美国变得伟大，认识到它长期以来如何伟大以及如何变得更加伟大，仍然很重要。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">听听特朗普选民的心声：那些被忽视的人、那些悲痛的人、那些末日卷轴的人、那些想要有所作为的人、那些想要在一个更美好的世界里养家糊口的人。那些投票反对特朗普的人也符合这些相同的描述。对于特朗普分歧的对立双方来说，尊重对方的意见至关重要，这样我们才能在不被政治操纵者利用的情况下找到解决美国问题的办法。你我对我们各自的政治领域并不缺乏幻想。难道我们不应该重新审视这些幻想，而不是瞧不起特朗普的追随者吗？</p>鲍勃提出了民粹主义理论：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">民粹主义运动源于对文化和经济状况的普遍不满以及政府无力处理公众关切。这是有魅力的独裁领导人提供快速而简单的解决方案的沃土。尽管特朗普可能是一个品格低下的人，但对他的许多支持者来说，他似乎是一种需要的斗士——一个不遵守规则的人，因为规则被认为是问题所在。詹姆斯·麦迪逊会感到悲伤和失望。</p>贾莉拉分析了她认为特朗普支持者的动机：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">特朗普的支持者真诚地相信他是被陷害的，不仅因为多年来他一直在向他们宣传自己的信念，而且因为他们必须相信这一点，以免陷入严重抑郁。想象一下，你投身于一个错误的宗教，或者一个不成功的职业，或者一个糟糕的伴侣。想象一下，与你的终生朋友和强烈反对你的选择的成年子女失去关系。当你付出巨大代价致力于某件事时，很难承认你的承诺是徒劳的。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">我认为这么多人坚称特朗普是无辜的，这并不奇怪。当然，我确实相信他是一个骗子，腐败程度足以犯下他被指控的罪行。但真正的革命人物却总是因虚假指控而被关押。纳尔逊·曼德拉和圣雄甘地被指控、定罪和监禁。今天，大多数理性的人都认为他们的监禁是不公正的，国家有能力捏造证据来指控威胁社会秩序的公众人物。特朗普的支持者只是在不合理的背景下应用合理的想法。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">自由派和进步派似乎并不热衷于接受悔改的特朗普支持者。更换团队没有什么好处。这是一个非常高的成本。团结起来支持特朗普的城镇与自由派城镇一样热衷于取消文化。没有人愿意在教堂里面对一群邻居，或者在杂货店里被指控支持堕落。同侪压力可能让很多人守规矩。</p>丹认为，“大多数人认为选民会关注候选人的记录和个性”，但“真正重要的是候选人是否赋予选民身份。”他解释说：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">选民因为对候选人的支持而成为“某人”。特朗普在这方面比 50 年来的任何候选人都做得更好。对于那些世界被精英摧毁的选民，特朗普说：<em>你们很重要。成为这场运动的一部分，你就可以勇敢地面对精英。你可以和我一起恢复你的生活，并再次成为一个大人物</em>。特朗普的法律案件很容易被合理化，因为他个人愿意为代表所有认为他验证自己的生活并再次赋予他们身份的人而付出代价。对于他的支持者来说，他正在为“事业”做出牺牲。</p>克里斯托弗斥责特朗普的批评者，因为他认为特朗普的批评者不了解他们的国家：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">特朗普的支持者认为，经济和文化游戏被操纵了。特朗普的支持者不同意向小孩子传授性别知识，也不同意向易受影响的未成年人提供变性护理，并因此被贴上了贬义的标签。他们认为将佛罗里达州法律标榜为“不要说同性恋”——尽管大多数美国人可能会支持佛罗里达州为确保适合年龄的教育而做出的努力的内容和意图——是错误的。同样，当有人支持执法或反对平权行动时，他们就会被贴上“种族主义者”的标签，即使有原则上的理由提出异议。特朗普利用了玩被操纵游戏所带来的挫败感。特朗普的支持者认为特朗普正在挑战排斥他们及其观点的文化和经济体系。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">精英和媒体需要停止将特朗普的支持者视为边缘群体。特朗普在 2020 年获得的选票比奥巴马（2008 年）还要多，在 2020 年排名第二，仅次于拜登。 2024 年大选很可能即将结束。特朗普所涉及的问题并不是转瞬即逝的。</p>杰夫描述了他在科罗拉多州担任零售经理时观察到的一种选民，他在一家迎合特朗普投票人群的商店里观察到：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">他们是白人、工薪阶层，对事物非常了解并能解决它，但他们并不重视教育，因为教育在美国是系统化的。他们的日常用语非常违规，但总的来说是模范公民。对我来说，最值得注意的情绪通常是这样表达的：“投票给一位坐牢的总统不是很好吗？！”他们出于反应而为他辩护：这“不受欢迎”，并且他们对机器感到愤怒。想想支持尼克松是否是你能做的最“朋克摇滚”的事情。</p>帕特里夏分享了她如何成为民主党人，并描述了她观察到的一些特朗普支持者：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">我今年90岁了，是一名退休的医院管理人员。我和已故的丈夫在加利福尼亚州的共和党家庭中长大，并以这种方式投票，直到我们目睹了比尔·克林顿的弹劾，亲眼目睹了共和党的卑鄙和虚伪。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">从那时起我们就投票给民主党了。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">我的同祖母今年 89 岁了。她 22 岁时从阿根廷移民过来，所以你可能会认为她一闻到威权主义者的味道就认出了他们，但事实并非如此，她喜欢特朗普。她喜欢看<em>《学徒》</em>和《福克斯》。她的朋友们通过电子邮件传播他们在网上找到的疯狂东西。她拥有博士学位。从事教育工作并在大学任教多年。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">我有一位 65 岁的姻亲，住在加利福尼亚州奥兰治县，他的生意很成功。一个聪明人，但没有受过正规教育。他是特朗普的支持者，主要是因为税收。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">我的孙女和她的丈夫最近从西雅图地区搬到爱达荷州北部，因为他们不喜欢华盛顿州的规定。他们认为特朗普不是一个好人，但与自由主义非常一致——他们不希望政府干涉他们的自由，所以他们认为特朗普是唯一的选择。两人都是大学毕业生。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">除了他们之外，我还观察到，有些人似乎具有“遗传”特征，他们只是喜欢看到一个人“粘”在别人身上。特朗普特别擅长嘲讽。</p>尼克认为他年轻和右倾的经历帮助他理解了对特朗普的支持：<br><br><p> 2016 年之前，我认为自己是保守派。在大学期间，如果我试图对移民等话题发表不同的看法，我会感到被嘲笑和瞧不起。我决定我的两个选择是遭到蔑视或闭嘴。我知道我不是唯一一个。我的好朋友创办了一个俱乐部，将自由派和保守派聚集在一起讨论重大问题。他竭尽全力让保守派出现，但就是没能实现。我并不感到惊讶，因为我不认为我是唯一一个因为害怕被“取消”而无法分享的保守派，或者因为不遵循主流自由主义路线而被称为种族主义者或偏执狂。尽管特朗普有令人震惊的不民主和不道德行为，但共和党人仍然团结在他周围，因为他们在他身上看到了自己，一个保守派，不断因其信仰而受到自由派的嘲笑，除非他真正发声。我不认为所有保守派都是像特朗普一样渴望权力的独裁者，而且我认为他们中的大多数人也不同意他的观点。但我确实认为，当我们在某人身上看到自己时，我们会倾向于支持他们。身份政治在两党中都存在；也许我们看到的只是保守的版本。</p> T. 认为我们正在目睹对文化变革的反应：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">我是西部一座进步城市的建筑师。我讨厌唐纳德·特朗普，但我理解为什么我在田纳西州的姻亲毫无保留地支持他。让我感到困惑的是，我认识的许多聪明、自由派的人都不明白这一点。您还记得 2016 年大选后，希拉里输给了美国历史上最糟糕的总统候选人时，一片寂静吗？民主党人进行了几个月的认真自省，但很快就冷却下来，从那以后我再也没有听到过类似的声音。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;">我认为我们缺乏理解是因为我们大多数人无法设身处地为弱势特朗普选民着想。你会看到一股席卷而来的政治、经济和文化浪潮席卷而来——它不仅代表着改变，还代表着对你生活方式的蔑视和对你自我意识的破坏。我并不是说这是真的，但印象是非常真实的。这是文化帝国主义，当我们谈论中产阶级化时，我们非常理解这一点，但当入侵力量来自我们这边时，我们就完全忽略了这一点。毕竟，如果我们面对的是一种嘲笑我们的宗教、吸走我们最聪明的年轻人并让他们相信我们无知无知、将我们出卖给全球经济、提倡对成千上万的人来说是禁忌的生活方式，我们会有什么感受？几年，如果我们不同意就取消我们？它符合过去 250 年来被现代工业社会蹂躏的原住民文化的经历。那些田纳西人正在被一个骗子卖掉一张货物清单，但我们却陷害了他们。</p> JP describes the Trump support of his loved ones:<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> They do not go to Trump rallies, nor do they look or sound like those abhorrent Trump supporters you see in interview-reel compilations. They are compassionate, kind to strangers, and even have friends in people of all political stripes. We are a racially diverse bunch: Black, Hispanic, and white. And yet, these same people believe in their bones that for every lie Donald Trump has told, the liberal media has told more. For every crime Donald Trump has committed, the liberal elites in our politics and culture have committed more.</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> And regarding his claims of election fraud, despite lack of hard evidence, they feel in their gut that he is right on some level. I doubt I could do or say anything to convince them otherwise.</p> Paul describes the pull of tribes:<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> Part of being a human being is wanting to belong. One way we do that is to identify with someone or something. Passionate sports fans are a good example. And once we link our identity, our sense of who we are, to those teams, we look at everything about those teams through a positive perspective. People have identified with Trump and now their well-being and self-image are tied to him. That prevents them from viewing any reality other than the one that he creates. It will take some sort of disruption to break up with him, but it doesn&#39;t look like that will occur. When their identity is at risk, the most comfortable path is to stay with Trump and distort new data to fit their views.</p> Michael believes that demographic insecurity is a factor:<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> I suspect that support for Trump is rooted in people&#39;s fears of becoming a minority and suffering economic demise due to competition from immigration by humans who are unlike them.</p> Tim believes that Trump&#39;s appeal is even simpler:<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> Give someone a reason to feel good about their anger and resentment and you can gain their loyalty.</p></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 16:17:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/13-readers-on-what-trump-voters-want/674961/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/13-readers-on-what-trump-voters-want/674961/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Don’t Overthink Gardening]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> You don&#39;t need a massive garden and a green thumb. Just put a pit in a pot.<br> So many of my friends are what I&#39;d call “garden curious.” The dream is simple: ample backyard space where they can grow their own food, compost, and live out their most cherished ideas for a greener life. The reality: Time and space are limited.<br><br> But no one needs to wait for the perfect conditions to grow something. In my own experience with Lazy-Girl Gardening, I&#39;ve seen the best results when I&#39;ve embraced low-stakes experiments focused on food I love. I have grown tomatoes, peppers, lettuce greens, and herbs in my apartment; today, lemon-balm and mint plants I started from seed adorn my kitchen windowsill, and for the past two summers, I have grown sungold tomatoes in containers on the sliver of concrete I refer to as my “terrace.” Though it won&#39;t bear fruit for the next five years, my pride and joy is a three-foot-tall plant I grew from a grocery-store avocado&#39;s pit.<br><br> Growing vegetables at a modest scale allowed me to reduce the carbon emissions associated with my diet in a small but meaningful way. My plants have saved me a few trips to the grocery store, to buy food shipped in from far away. It has also reconnected me to a sense of seasonality. And gardening, no matter the scale, is downright relaxing.<br><br><br> Even if you don&#39;t have an expansive permanent space to garden, consider following these three principles to start. Practical apartment gardening is an exercise in living better <em>right now</em> , instead of waiting for the right circumstances. The climate is changing fast enough that the best conditions for gardening might be whenever you start; paying attention to plants and how they grow will put you that much more in touch with those shifts.<br><br> <strong>Embrace the Small</strong><br><br> In the world of plant-based lifestyles—think juicy monstera plants spread across the pages of <em>Homes &amp; Gardens</em> and viral <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.popsugar.com/fitness/oprah-winfrey-video-her-gigantic-cabbage-on-instagram-47496524">photos of Oprah</a> harvesting ginormous vegetables—bigger is better. Against the standard established by the backyard jungles of HGTV, which I watched obsessively as a newbie gardener while living in an 1,100-square-foot unit that I shared with two roommates, any plants I grew suddenly looked meager.<br><br> Hoping to compete with plant parents in my circle and, yes, Oprah, I began to devise ingenious ways to grow plants in the limited space I had. I lined my room almost wall to wall with plant projects: a few attempts to grow peppers here. A trial of various broccoli varieties there. I even installed two hanging baskets in the ceiling, hoping to use the vertical space to grow butterhead lettuce. One day I awoke and couldn&#39;t open my bedroom door. If I didn&#39;t start thinking smaller, I&#39;d be living on top of my plants, instead of among them.<br><br> Embracing small plants inevitably means embracing container gardening and the plants that are well suited for it. In pursuit of the biggest, lushest veggies, I&#39;d failed to consider their sunlight and spatial needs. Plants that have a wide spread (lettuce), grow tall (peppers), or have deep root systems (carrots) aren&#39;t necessarily ideal for confinement. I ditched the large, leafy plants. I went with herbs.<br><br> “When it comes to getting people interested in gardening, I always start with herbs because it&#39;s something that most people are familiar with, and they grow well in small spaces,” Cynthia Nazario-Leary, an environmental horticulture agent in northern Florida, told me.<br><br> As a daily tea drinker, I wanted to grow herbs that I could easily harvest, dry, and steep. That meant lavender, which can grow indoors year-round, and mint, which grows at weedlike speed. These thrived beautifully in full sun, planted in separate pots. As I became more comfortable growing on a smaller scale, I expanded into cilantro and rosemary, which I cook with frequently. When my mint and cilantro started to wilt in the colder months of winter, I misted their leaves in between waterings to retain their moisture. This intentional act of care made me mindful of how my own needs shift in the winter, when shorter, frigid days make me crave sunlight and warmth.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/08/tea-time/535590/">Read: Britain&#39;s great tea heist</a><br><br> If you&#39;re dead set on growing vegetables, containers can still work. But not without trade-offs. If you don&#39;t mind sacrificing some space, using large planters (five gallons or bigger) allows you to accommodate a broader range of plants with varying root depths and leaf spans. Fabric grow bags are a lighter alternative to plastic or terra-cotta pots but can dry out your plants, so you&#39;ll need to water more frequently. My favorite container-gardening hack is to reuse containers that I&#39;d otherwise throw away. Takeout containers are great for this, but you can also use plastic margarine or yogurt containers and milk cartons. After adding some holes in the bottom for drainage, you now have a solid container in which to start vegetable seedlings, propagate ornamental plants, or even grow microgreens.<br><br> Container gardening does require a little more thought than just sticking a plant in the ground, in the sunlight, if your goal is to reduce your carbon emissions. I use organic, peat-free potting-soil mixtures in all of my containers, for instance. Many commercial potting soil contains peat moss, commonly sourced from bogs in Canada, which are exceptional carbon sinks. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/home/2023/04/05/peat-soil-mixes-harm-environment/">Harvesting any amount of peat has potential climate impacts</a> . And as Nazario-Leary told me, “Plants that develop fruit or flowers require a lot of energy in the form of sunlight,” so growing plants like tomatoes and peppers indoors might mean you need to “invest in a good LED grow light.” Although LED bulbs are more efficient than incandescent lights (which are now functionally <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/01/climate/incandescent-light-bulb-ban-leds.html">banned</a> in most cases, although that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.energy.gov/sites/default/files/2022-05/GSL%20Backstop%20Enforcement%20Webinar%20May%204%202022.pdf">does not apply to plant lights</a> ), these energy inputs add up.<br><br> <strong>Be Scrappy</strong><br><br> In addition to seeds, you can also grow new plants from old ones. Instead of tossing out the tips or ends of grocery-store root vegetables, I chuck them in water to encourage root formation, then transfer them to small pots in a sunny window. Plenty of us played around with this during the pandemic: For me, it worked especially well with staples such as garlic, ginger, celery, green onions, lettuce, and potatoes. I now regularly replant the white tips of grocery-store scallions and a few lettuce cores so I can harvest clippings for my cooking over several months.<br><br> Using food scraps as gardening material is a simple way to reduce your household food waste and extend the life of your groceries. Anne-Marie Bonneau, a chef and zero-waste-cookbook author, regularly recycles food scraps to regrow food directly or to use as compost.<br><br> “As I&#39;m prepping in the kitchen, it costs me nothing to set my scraps of green onion or leek aside, to soak in water and regrow in my kitchen,” Bonneau told me. Growth-inhibiting chemicals may be present on commercially grown vegetables, especially potatoes, but a thorough wash with soap and water should remove these.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/06/foraging-tours-medicinal-plants-popularity/674307/">Read: The missing piece of the foraging renaissance</a><br><br> All of this does have good climate math. Most produce grown in the US travels about <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wbur.org/news/2022/08/30/cooked-newsletter-buying-local-food-sustainable">1,500 miles before it&#39;s sold</a> . Containers and packaging generate 82 million tons of waste each year, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.epa.gov/facts-and-figures-about-materials-waste-and-recycling/containers-and-packaging-product-specific">according to the EPA</a> . The non-compostable produce stickers, mesh bags, and clam shells associated with fruits and vegetables certainly don&#39;t help. Bonneau, who has committed to a plastic-free life, ticked off for me the pluses of growing plants; they “eliminate packaging waste, shave off some food miles from what you&#39;re eating, and save a few dollars.”<br><br> But gardening isn&#39;t just about avoiding emissions: In the end, small experiments like these will change your carbon impact only a small amount. But I do it anyway. I may not be changing the climate with my small projects, but I do notice how our climate is shifting, and understand it more viscerally because I garden. As Robin Wall Kimmerer, a plant ecologist and author, wrote, “Paying attention is a form of reciprocity with the living world, receiving the gifts with open eyes and open heart.”<br><br> <strong>Stay in Your Zone</strong><br><br> As much as I loved the challenge of growing plants in my apartment, when I received a slot in a nearby community garden after a three-year wait, I couldn&#39;t believe my luck. Without thinking, I immediately replanted my indoor herb experiments—my rosemary, lavender, cilantro—in my new garden bed, hoping to capitalize on the longer days of sunlight and rainfall of early spring. But a week later, most of my herbs had turned to withered tendrils.<br><br> This new garden was a crash course in the importance of growing seasons. In my neck of New England, evening temperatures drop below freezing well into May. My rosemary plants especially had no chance against the spring frost.<br><br> Since this setback, I&#39;ve become obsessed with the US Department of Agriculture&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://planthardiness.ars.usda.gov/">Plant Hardiness Zone Map</a> , which categorizes every region in the country based on plant-growing conditions. The lower the zone number, the colder the temperatures in winter. In my region, hardiness zone six, beans, broccoli, lettuce greens, cauliflower, cucumbers, eggplant, peppers, and tomatoes do well in a growing season from May to October. For gardeners in the Pacific Northwest, which spans zones three through eight, winter vegetable production is possible thanks to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://catalog.extension.oregonstate.edu/sites/catalog/files/project/pdf/pnw548.pdf">oceanic weather patterns that bring more rainfall</a> . Growers in the Southwest, zones six through nine, should plant vegetables like okra, peppers, and eggplant, which grow well in the region&#39;s hot and sunny conditions.<br><br> Gardening indoors can help control the temperature, but there will always be some limit to what you can grow based on where you live. Becoming more familiar with growing seasons and bioregions gave me new awareness of the global food system that allows me to enjoy a tropical mango in December. Now I eat more in alignment with my region&#39;s growing season—prioritizing my own food and farmers&#39; markets when I can, opting for winter squash and root vegetables in colder months—which has pushed me toward a plant-based diet. For the average American, buying locally might achieve as much as a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/es702969f">4 to 5 percent reduction in household</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/es702969f">greenhouse gas</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/es702969f">emissions</a> , although other dietary changes—namely <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/vegetarian-vegan-eating-meat-consumption-animal-welfare/674150/">eating less meat</a> —are a more powerful way of shrinking your carbon footprint. If you grow a few herbs and then eat a steak for dinner every night, you&#39;re missing the point.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/05/pacific-northwest-heat-wave-record-breaking-wildfires/674076/">Read: Nowhere should expect a cool summer</a><br><br> Caring for the plants that feed me gives me a deep sense of place and the ways in which New England is changing. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mdpi.com/2225-1154/9/12/176">A 2021 study</a> revealed that New England is warming faster than the rest of the planet; experts predict that global warming will <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://19january2017snapshot.epa.gov/sites/production/files/2016-09/documents/climate-change-ma.pdf">lengthen the region&#39;s</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://19january2017snapshot.epa.gov/sites/production/files/2016-09/documents/climate-change-ma.pdf">growing season</a> . This could mean opportunities to produce fruits and vegetables that were previously difficult to grow, but also more extreme weather events and pests that can destroy crops.<br><br> Gardening has made these changes apparent to me. Having lost a few crops to sunscald from hotter days, or from blight and leaf miners, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/1402920/icode/">which now appear</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/1402920/icode/">with greater frequency</a> , I worry about farmers facing these challenges on a larger scale. Growing my own food in scrappy, small ways that honor the ecology of where I live reminds me just how much my own health as a human rests on the health of the plants that we grow.<br><br> <small><em>This story is part of the Atlantic Planet series supported by HHMI&#39;s Science and Educational Media Group.</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 16:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/gardening-beginning-principles/674962/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/gardening-beginning-principles/674962/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why You Should Worry About China’s Missing Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> If the world&#39;s best China experts can&#39;t figure out what happened to one of the country&#39;s most internationally recognizable officials, then imagine what else remains hidden behind the regime&#39;s closed doors. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/0w5yIh0TLXHmIJKsRPl91uCVhwQ=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/china_mystery_/original.jpg" alt="秦刚脸部的插图被中国国旗遮挡。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by The Atlantic.资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure> The disappearance of Chinese Foreign Minister Qin Gang has generated a torrent of speculation about what might have happened to him. The mystery points to a larger, and disconcerting, truth: We understand very little about the inner workings of Chinese politics at a moment when we need to know more than ever.<br><br> China&#39;s Communist regime has always been opaque. But the more China&#39;s global power rises, the more problematic the Communist Party&#39;s secrecy becomes. The decisions made in Beijing influence the wealth and welfare of billions of people, the health of the planet, and war and peace itself. Yet policy makers and diplomats around the world are too often left guessing about how these decisions are made, who is making them, and why.<br><br> The current Chinese leader, Xi Jinping, has further narrowed the already small window into the cloistered halls of power. “Secrecy is the default position of the Communist Party anyway, but it has been put on steroids under Xi,” Steve Tsang, the director of the SOAS China Institute at the University of London, told me.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/02/china-million-covid-deaths-communist-party/673177/">Read: Can a million Chinese people die and nobody know?</a><br><br> In the strained relationship between the United States and China, the dearth of reliable information about Beijing&#39;s circumstances and decision making could lead to dangerous misunderstandings. “This is a real problem in US-China relations,” Carl Minzner, a senior fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations who specializes in Chinese government, told me. “You start to lose your appreciation for what is actually taking place in China and why,” with the result that “it is always easy to ascribe the worst narrative” to China&#39;s actions.<br><br> The missing minister is a case in point. Qin Gang is a well-known figure in Washington, where he previously served as ambassador to the United States before being promoted to foreign minister in December. He has been widely seen as an up-and-coming politician and a Xi loyalist. He was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://multimedia.scmp.com/infographics/news/china/article/3195959/20th-central-committee-members/index.html">awarded</a> a seat on the powerful Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party in October.<br><br> In early July, Qin failed to appear at several important diplomatic meetings. China watchers took note as Beijing abruptly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/world/europes-top-diplomat-visit-china-july-10-2023-07-04/">canceled</a> a planned visit by the European Union&#39;s foreign-policy chief, and as China&#39;s foreign ministry later cited health issues as the reason Qin <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/wang-yi-represent-china-asean-raising-questions-over-qin-gang-whereabouts-2023-07-11/">did not attend</a> a summit with Southeast Asian nations.<br><br> Later that month, Qin was suddenly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/world/china/china-appoints-wang-yi-its-new-foreign-minister-replacing-absent-qin-gang-2023-07-25/">removed</a> as foreign minister and replaced by his predecessor, Wang Yi. Two days after the announcement, the foreign ministry spokesperson Mao Ning was asked about that decision at a briefing, and she offered no explanation, instead <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jul/27/qin-gang-china-foreign-ministry-transcript-missing-replaced">protesting</a> the “malicious hype of this matter.”<br><br> The government appears to be confused about how to present Qin&#39;s disappearance. After his dismissal, the foreign ministry began erasing Qin from its website, only to reverse course and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/neilthomas123/status/1684641904548282368">restore</a> the deleted references. Meanwhile, Qin&#39;s whereabouts remain unknown. He has not been seen in public since June 25.<br><br> Tsang attributes the obfuscation surrounding Qin to the Communist Party&#39;s tendency to place its own perceived interests ahead of concern for the international community or even the nation. “What the Chinese foreign minister does or doesn&#39;t do, or what happens to him, matters to the rest of the world,” Tsang said. “Does the Communist Party, in particular its core leader, give much of a monkey for this implication for the rest of the world? No.”<br><br> China watchers have stepped in to fill the information void with debate and speculation about Qin&#39;s apparent downfall. Conditioned by experience with official deception, many experts have suspected that something sinister is afoot. Perhaps Qin ran afoul of the party bosses and became the target of a purge, or was the subject of an investigation for unknown infractions. A narrative emerged that alleges Qin had an affair—and possibly a child—with a journalist at a Chinese-language television network. Though hardly moral paragons, China&#39;s top leaders frown upon such personal foibles if they can potentially compromise the Communist Party.<br><br> But the sex-scandal saga could just as easily be utter nonsense. Qin so far seems to have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/07/25/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang/">retained</a> his other, more influential, posts, including on the party&#39;s Central Committee, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/07/25/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang/">which</a> implies that politics may not be at play. Or that Xi has not yet decided on Qin&#39;s ultimate fate. Or that the party is trying to deflect criticism from Xi, who elevated Qin over more experienced officials, in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://chinadigitaltimes.net/2023/07/qin-gang-removed-as-foreign-minister-without-explanation/">hope</a> that the controversy blows over.<br><br> Or … who knows. But therein lies the big point. If the world&#39;s best China experts can&#39;t figure out what happened to one of China&#39;s most internationally recognizable officials, then imagine what else remains hidden behind the regime&#39;s closed doors.<br><br> The party prefers it that way. Michelle Mood, a longtime China expert at Kenyon College, commented to me that the Qin affair reveals “the limits of the knowable with regard to China.”<br><br> Xi has consistently tightened the state&#39;s grip on information within China. In recent years, censors have suppressed discussion of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/china-shuts-social-media-accounts-over-market-and-other-rumors-1.1946506">economic</a> policy, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/technology-china-media-social-media-taiwan-348cab147964f24ccf83907403d4c84a">LGBTQ issues</a> , and even <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/06/tech/china-weibo-k-pop/index.html">K-pop</a> . Regulators recently finalized new rules for chatbots run by artificial intelligence that, though less stringent than an earlier draft, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/technology/china-issues-temporary-rules-generative-ai-services-2023-07-13/">insist</a> the content generated must be in line with the country&#39;s socialist values. In May, authorities detained a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/05/25/china-comedy-censorship-performing-arts/">comedian</a> who told a joke about China&#39;s military and fined the company he worked for $2 million—a sign of just how sensitive the state can be.<br><br> Xi&#39;s government has shown heightened paranoia about what the world knows about China as well. Earlier this year, a prominent database of Chinese academic research <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thechinaproject.com/2023/07/06/cut-off-from-chinas-data-and-info-overseas-academics-analysts-get-crafty/">curtailed</a> foreign access to its platform. Vincent Brussee and Kai von Carnap, analysts at the Mercator Institute for China Studies, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://merics.org/en/comment/amended-anti-espionage-law-aims-curate-chinas-own-narrative">argued</a> in a recent paper that a newly amended anti-espionage law could target “almost anyone who exchanges information with international counterparts” and that the aim is “to make the Communist Party the sole narrator of China&#39;s story.” The state security ministry, in its first post on a social-media account, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/08/02/china/china-security-ministry-on-wechat-intl-hnk/index.html">encouraged</a> Chinese citizens to get involved in antispying efforts by spying on others.<br><br> Tsang argues that the trend toward greater secrecy is a consequence of Xi&#39;s centralization of power. “Unlike in collective leadership, when the top leader can hide behind collective decisions, there is nowhere for Xi Jinping to hide,” Tsang told me. Exerting control over information through secrecy allows a strongman to protect his stature and to claim infallibility: “If nobody knows what actually happened, you were never wrong, because they can never find evidence to show that you were wrong,” Tsang said.<br><br> But in truth Xi has often been wrong, and China is suffering for it. His policies have contributed to a sagging economy, hostile relations with most of the world&#39;s major powers, and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/06/-china-pessimism-economy-censorship/674556/">growing pessimism</a> about the nation&#39;s future. With a shortage of good news to boast of, Xi preserves his political standing by wielding ever greater influence over narratives about China.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/06/-china-pessimism-economy-censorship/674556/">Read: The end of optimism in China</a><br><br> The effort to stave off criticism and bad news has led the leadership to treat topics of discussion that were once considered relatively safe ground—such as economic policy—as potentially threatening. To Minzner, the Council on Foreign Relations fellow, this rise in sensitivity toward formerly innocuous subject matter is evidence of a broader trend toward “securitization,” in which the system responds to economic and social pressures by locking down access to information. Put another way, according to Mood, the Communist Party&#39;s “political legitimacy, no longer supported by a growing economy, is now based on censorship to control information and knowledge.”<br><br> The thickening shroud of secrecy is a problem not only for policy makers around the world, but also for those governing China. Domestic officials responsible for addressing the consequences of the country&#39;s slowing growth and social pressures are not talking to one another, says Mary Gallagher, a specialist in Chinese politics at the University of Michigan. “I don&#39;t think the system is as responsive as it used to be, and I think that will be very problematic based on how many problems it needs to solve in the next five to 10 years,” Gallagher told me.<br><br> In other words, Xi&#39;s secrecy could imperil his ambitions for China and its role in the world. The Qin Gang mystery is thus a warning sign of profound and dangerous weaknesses in the Chinese political system that have emerged under Xi&#39;s rule and are likely to continue to deepen.<br><br> The Qin affair “points to this issue of elite instability that I think we&#39;ll see more of in China,” Gallagher said. “We don&#39;t know the process by which the next leader is going to be chosen, and we also don&#39;t know when the next leader will be chosen. That just makes the people who are jockeying for that position and of course the people around them just more prone to internal struggles.”<br><br> The world will likely have to guess at those machinations as well. “I really worry that we are moving into an era where people understand less and less what&#39;s actually taking place in China,” Minzner told me. “I find it very difficult to figure out how this gets reversed.”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 15:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/qin-gang-china-missing-foreign-minister/674954/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/qin-gang-china-missing-foreign-minister/674954/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Anti-California]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> How Montana performed a housing miracle <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/0M3YEVBin4tmioMgQs-kA-LKfK0=/0x0:4962x2791/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/bwGettyImages_1487414021_3/original.jpg" alt="科罗拉多州" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Justin Sullivan / Getty</figcaption></figure> <small><i data-stringify-type="italic">This article was featured in One Story to Read Today, a newsletter in which our editors recommend a single must-read from</i> The Atlantic <i data-stringify-type="italic">, Monday through Friday.</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sign up for it here.</a></i></small><br><br> I <span class="smallcaps">n 2015</span> , a physical therapist named Nathan Dugan moved to Whitefish, Montana, and fell in love with the place. How could you not? The glaciers, the pine air, the small-town feel. Whitefish was always expensive: When he first got there, Dugan camped on and off for a month before he found an affordable home. But it got far more expensive during the pandemic, when wealthy retirees and digital nomads flooded the tiny town&#39;s tiny housing market. Out-of-staters were making cash offers on homes, sight unseen. Airbnbs started going for Bay Area prices. Rentals dried up. This has become a familiar story across America, where the housing crisis has gotten so severe that even rural communities in northern Montana are feeling the pinch.<br><br> Here&#39;s another familiar story: Seeking to capitalize on the real-estate gold rush, a developer proposed building a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://dailyinterlake.com/news/2022/feb/07/whitefish-council-faces-decision-big-mountain-hous/">handsome 318-unit community</a> just north of downtown, on Whitefish Lake. The property would include a series of low-slung apartment buildings and townhomes, including units reserved for low-income families. Whitefish&#39;s residents freaked. Hundreds submitted letters to the town&#39;s planning committee. Local philanthropists, some billionaires, reportedly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://dailyinterlake.com/news/2022/feb/02/donors-threaten-pull-support-if-whitefish-housing-/">threatened to pull</a> their support from local nonprofits if city officials did not <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/giacomotognini/2022/02/16/how-billionaires-helped-kill-a-housing-development-in-a-montana-ski-town/?sh=cc3d2e1d4b72">nix the proposal</a> . Nearly 200 people showed up at a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cityofwhitefish.org/AgendaCenter/ViewFile/Minutes/_10212021-284">marathon public meeting</a> , one of several, to argue about, and mostly against, the project: It would look too tall, pollute the lake, pollute the night sky with light, change the neighborhood&#39;s character, stress the community&#39;s schools and medical services, destroy wildlife habitats, and increase traffic, which would interrupt snow plows and endanger families fleeing from forest fires. The town rejected the proposal.<br><br> Dugan was at that meeting and left incensed. “There&#39;s a gut reaction in places like this: <em>All development is bad, and we need to stop any development to maintain what we have,</em> ” he told me. “But the people who showed up to that meeting were all older and generally very wealthy.” They made it sound like the new development would ruin their lives, he said. But those people were doing fine. They already had a home in Whitefish.<br><br> Here&#39;s where things get different. NIMBYs have throttled the supply of homes across the country. In Montana, the state government was not just paying attention but primed to do something about it. At the same time that Dugan was steaming over his neighbors in Whitefish, analysts in Helena were worrying about the displacement of middle-class families, and politicians in Bozeman were hearing complaints about long commutes. “I can&#39;t do a town hall in any community in Montana and not have the affordability of housing come up,” Governor Greg Gianforte told me. “Housing prices have just been out of control.”<br><br> Last July, Gianforte created a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deq.mt.gov/about/Housing-Task-Force">housing task force</a> , bringing together homebuilders, politicians, experts, and advocates, including Dugan, who had gone on to found a housing nonprofit called Shelter WF. In October, the group delivered a series of proposals to state officials; in December, to local officials. Montana&#39;s legislature debated a set of bills based on those recommendations. Then it passed them this spring. The state transformed its land-use policies. It set itself up for dense development. It did this on a bipartisan basis and at warp speed.<br><br> Montana&#39;s just one state. But it did something—and maybe enough—to fix its housing crisis.<br><br> O <span class="smallcaps">ver the past decade</span> and change, the country&#39;s housing shortage has spread from coastal cities to suburbs and satellite cities to rural communities and small towns in the Mountain West, the plains, the interior South. Fannie Mae estimates that the country needs 4.4 million <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fanniemae.com/media/45106/display">more homes</a> . The National Association of Realtors <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nar.realtor/magazine/real-estate-news/biden-administration-takes-aim-at-america-s-housing-shortage">puts the number at</a> 5.5 million. But the country is not building enough homes to close the gap, or even keep up with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://usafacts.org/articles/population-growth-has-outpaced-home-construction-for-20-years/">population growth</a> .<br><br> Millions of families are stuck in apartments they do not want to live in, paying prices they cannot afford. Eventually, many decamp for low-cost, low-wage regions of the country. “Even before the pandemic, there was an increasing trend of people leaving expensive coastal areas like San Francisco, Los Angeles, and New York for more affordable places,” Daryl Fairweather, the chief economist at Redfin, told me. “Then the pandemic hit, and the trend accelerated.”<br><br> In recent years, that migration has buoyed or battered Montana, depending on how you look at it. The state&#39;s population surged 1.6 percent from mid-2020 to mid-2021, faster than that of 47 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2021/2021-population-estimates.html">other states</a> . Montana added nearly 20,000 residents while it permitted just 3,000 new <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/MTBP1FH">single-unit homes</a> . Home prices climbed by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/MTSTHPI">nearly 50 percent</a> in a matter of months.<br><br> When the pandemic hit, Montana already had a housing shortage; in fact, it had a few of them. First, a dilapidation problem. Building new housing in Montana&#39;s rural reaches is expensive, which leaves many residents occupying decaying and at times dangerous units. (This is a particular problem on Montana&#39;s American Indian reservations.) “If you look at population numbers and counts of housing units in these rural places, it doesn&#39;t <em>look</em> that bad,” Andrew Aurand of the National Low Income Housing Coalition told me. “But when you look at the <em>quality</em> of the housing, the safety of the housing, and the extent to which families are doubling up, the housing crisis is severe.”<br><br> Second, the tight market in resort, gateway, and second-home communities. Coastal-city billionaires and rich retirees keep buying up ranches and lodges in Montana. Their shmancy consumer spending creates jobs. But the people working those jobs end up living in campers close by or in homes far, far away, because there is just not enough housing.<br><br> Third, a shortage of affordable homes in Montana&#39;s population centers, such as Billings and Missoula. “The math does not work” for homebuilders to create low-income housing anywhere in the country absent government subsidies, Jeffrey Lubell, the director of housing and community initiatives for Abt Associates, told me. The math especially does not work in Montana, where frozen ground shortens the construction season, and where a lack of skilled tradespeople drives up costs.<br><br> These problems collided with the state&#39;s pandemic-era population surge. “I started looking around and thinking, <em>Holy cow, prices are going up</em> ,” Christopher Dorrington, the director of the Montana Department of Environmental Quality and the chair of Gianforte&#39;s housing task force, told me. The state suddenly had a noticeable homeless population; town squares and vacant lots filled with tents in the summertime. All but the very wealthiest families started feeling strained. “You couldn&#39;t move, because supply was so short,” Adam Hertz, a real-estate developer and former member of Montana&#39;s house, told me.<br><br> Gianforte said that the answer was obvious to him: Montana had a supply crisis. It needed a supply solution. His task force soon figured out how to get Montana more housing: Make it possible for folks to build housing units by right, rather than having every development go through a miserable, expensive process of negotiation. Encourage dense development in already dense areas. Cut red tape. Indeed, Montana already had pretty loose <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://realestate.wharton.upenn.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/558.pdf">building regulations</a> , and legislators loosened them even further—functionally banning single-family zoning and preventing towns and cities from adding onerous zoning policies, among many other changes and investments.<br><br> “We obviously did not anticipate being able to get the big wins we did,” Kendall Cotton, the founder of the local think tank the Frontier Institute and a driving force behind the housing bills, told me. “We thought maybe there might be one bill that passed. We ended up getting almost everything that we were asking for.”<br><br> Montana&#39;s policies aren&#39;t perfect. There still isn&#39;t enough incentive for developers to create low-income housing units, experts told me. Housing costs won&#39;t decline immediately, because building takes time (and because high interest rates have frozen the development pipeline). Montana has weak tenant protections and too few resources for struggling renters, antipoverty advocates said.<br><br> Still, housing experts around the country are cheering. Montana now arguably has the most pro-development, pro-housing set of policies of any state. How did this policy phenomenon happen, and so fast?<br><br> The explanation has something to do with the nature of Montana&#39;s housing crisis, and something to do with the nature of Montana itself. The fact that so many people in such a small state found themselves affected at once pushed legislators to act. “We were victims of our own success,” Hertz, the developer and former state representative, told me. “We&#39;ve been having all of these discussions about how to get people to move to Montana and start a business here: <em>How do we get more tourism in Montana? How do we get tech businesses here?</em> We got the demand, and wow, we got caught totally flat-footed on the supply side.”<br><br> Politics, for once, helped too. Montana had lower housing prices and fewer roadblocks to development than other states to begin with. Republicans with a strong libertarian streak, like Gianforte himself, are a powerful bloc, and happen to be the kind of folks thrilled to slash red tape. Joining them were anti-sprawl environmentalists, student activists, urban-density advocates, real-estate developers, and antipoverty liberals, creating a coalition spanning from the far left to the far right. The fact that Gianforte pushed so hard on the issue and that Montana&#39;s legislature meets only once every two years put more pressure on those elected officials to get something big done.<br><br> Yet perhaps the biggest motivating factor—one mentioned by nearly every Montanan I spoke with—was California. Montana did not want sprawl ruining its wildlands, as happened in the Central Valley and along the Pacific Coast. Montana did not want San Francisco&#39;s sky-high inequality and huge homeless population. Montana did not want middle-class families squeezed out, as they were in Oakland and San Diego. Montana did not want to throttle its own economy, as the Bay Area did.<br><br> “If you have single-family zoning and bury your head, you will eventually face San Francisco&#39;s problems. It&#39;s not just the high cost of housing. It&#39;s a high cost of living, wealth inequality, homelessness, and crime,” Fairweather of Redfin said. “All cities should look at San Francisco as an example of what happens when you do nothing.” Montana did, benefiting from California&#39;s missteps and learning from its YIMBY advocates.<br><br> Many other communities are doing the same. Washington and Maine are banning <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/was-new-ban-on-single-family-zoning-exempts-some-of-seattles-wealthiest-neighborhoods/">single-family zoning</a> , as Oregon did in 2019. A number of cities are allowing single-room-occupancy buildings, getting rid of parking minimums, and letting homeowners build second properties on their lots. YIMBY groups are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/where-pro-housing-groups-are-emerging/">blanketing the country</a> , pushing for denser development. Dugan&#39;s is one of them. He&#39;s hopeful that the state&#39;s new policies will increase the housing supply in Whitefish, where he and his partner just—finally—bought a home.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 15:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/rural-montana-housing-crisis-supply/674950/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/rural-montana-housing-crisis-supply/674950/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[San Francisco Has a Problem With Robotaxis]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一个世纪前，城市屈服于汽油动力汽车。他们会对自动驾驶汽车做同样的事情吗？<br><span class="smallcaps">几周前</span>，软件工程师丹·阿弗根<span class="smallcaps">(</span> Dan Afergan) 在旧金山内里士满社区的 540 Rogues 酒吧遇到了几个朋友。当阿弗根和他的同伴们准备饮料时，有人走进来，带来了一些不寻常的消息：“外面有一艘游轮，上面粘着一个圆锥体。”<br><br>阿弗根走到外面查看。果然，通用汽车持有多数股权的 Cruise 公司的一辆自动驾驶出租车停在了街道中央，危险警示灯闪烁。机器人出租车的引擎盖上栖息着一个亮橙色的圆锥体。<br><br> “当时，我认为这是一个愚蠢的恶作剧，”阿弗根后来告诉我。 “但一位朋友说，‘不，我听说过这件事。’直到那时我才知道还有一群人反对自动驾驶汽车。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/12/7-arguments-against-the-autonomous-vehicle-utopia/578638/">阅读：反对自动驾驶汽车乌托邦的七个论点</a><br><br>阿菲尔根目睹的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://sfstandard.com/2023/07/07/we-spoke-to-one-of-the-activists-coning-cruise-and-waymo-robotaxis-in-san-francisco/#:~:text=A%20group%20of%20San%20Franciscans,cone%20on%20the%20vehicle's%20hood.&amp;text=One%20member%20of%20Safe%20Street,a%20dozen%20cars%20so%20far.">“圆锥形”</a>是安全街叛乱组织发起的运动的一部分，安全街叛乱组织是当地的一个激进组织，此前以组织抗议活动支持<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://sf.streetsblog.org/2022/01/26/valencia-street-just-a-minute-pilot-protest">自行车道建设</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tiktok.com/@sfstandard/video/7242746017781681454">公共交通资助而</a>闻名。现在其成员已将注意力转向机器人出租车。根据新闻网站<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://missionloca.s3.amazonaws.com/mission/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/DMV-numbers-on-AVs.pdf"><em>Mission Local</em></a>报道的政府数据，Cruise 及其竞争对手 Waymo（谷歌母公司 Alphabet 的子公司）在加州总共运营<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://missionloca.s3.amazonaws.com/mission/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/DMV-numbers-on-AVs.pdf">571 辆</a>自动驾驶出租车。用户可以通过应用程序向他们打招呼。服务集中在旧金山，那里的公司受到加州公用事业委员会施加的各种限制。尽管旧金山<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2023-06-23/san-francisco-police-union-backs-sf-fire-chief-on-waymo-cruise-robotaxi-interference">警察</a><u>工会</u>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://sfstandard.com/2023/06/07/san-francisco-transit-chief-blasts-cruise-waymo-robotaxis-unsafe/">交通</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/transit/sf-fire-chief-rips-cruise-waymo-ahead-of-possible-expansion/article_903ab0d4-1122-11ee-aafd-5745a3aacbe2.html">消防</a>部门对机器人出租车阻塞交通和阻碍紧急车辆的不良习惯表示反对，但这两家公司现在希望 CPUC 取消这些限制。该委员会已两次推迟做出决定，但预计将于明天进行投票。<br><br>在意识到在引擎盖上放置一个简单的橙色锥体似乎会使最先进的自动驾驶汽车瘫痪后，Safe Street Rebel 发布了一段 TikTok <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/SafeStreetRebel/status/1676695665278337024?s=20">视频</a>，鼓励旧金山居民亲自尝试。 <span class="smallcaps">Hell no. “我们不同意这样做”</span> ，在城市街道上的机器人出租车视频中，一个标题这样说道。当这段视频在社交媒体上疯传时，Cruise 和 Waymo 并没有感到好笑， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/transit/cruise-waymo-pan-tiktok-of-sf-cars-being-disabled-by-cones/article_7dd044ae-1cee-11ee-8a55-5b17abbb30dc.html">他们威胁</a>说，如果有人在他们的汽车上放置锥体，就会报警。<br><br>人们可能会认为机器人出租车的游击式圆锥形锥体是反科技反弹的又一个迹象，或者只是旧金山就是旧金山。但这些叙述低估了当前骚动的重要性。城市居民、科技公司和政府官员第一次就自动驾驶汽车是否以及如何适应人口稠密的城市展开争论。这是一场现在就需要进行的对话，而自动驾驶汽车技术仍处于开发阶段，并且在它重塑旧金山和整个美国城市的生活之前。一个世纪前，美国开始重新规划其城市，以容纳那个时代最具未来感的车辆——私人汽车——从那时起，美国的决策就破坏了城市生活。机器人出租车可能具有同样的变革性，这使得谨慎行事变得更加必要。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">在机器人出租车故事的乌托邦版本中</span>，自动驾驶电动汽车的旅行变得如此实惠、轻松和愉快，以至于许多人决定放弃拥有自己的汽车。由于旧金山靠近硅谷，并且是众多投资者和科技记者的家园，因此这座城市是新兴技术备受瞩目、高风险的试验场。对于自动驾驶汽车来说，这也是一个比<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://techcrunch.com/2023/05/04/waymo-doubles-robotaxi-service-area-in-phoenix-in-bid-to-grow-driverless-trips-tenfold/">凤凰城</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2022/12/7/23496383/uber-motional-av-robotaxi-las-vegas-ridehail">拉斯维加斯</a>等广阔的地方更具挑战性的环境，因为这些地方的行人、骑自行车的人和公共交通乘客较少。<br><br>自动驾驶汽车的新颖性是其吸引力的关键部分。 “游客给我拍照，所以我感觉自己像个小名人，”一位名叫 David Anderson 的旧金山居民告诉我，他说他每周都会多次请求乘坐 Waymo。除了令人惊叹的因素之外，这些公司还提供类似于叫车的服务，研究人员发现这<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/uber-lyft-traffic-congestion-car-ownership-study/">会加剧城市拥堵</a>，并使<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-24/do-uber-and-lyft-really-drive-down-transit-ridership">乘客远离公共交通</a>。<br><br>对于机器人出租车和其他自动驾驶车辆来说，最有吸引力的论据也许是人类驾驶员很容易犯错。上个月，Waymo 联合首席执行官在《<em>旧金山纪事报》</em>上发表了一篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://t.co/SsJQwk0qEj">专栏文章</a>，赞扬了该公司车辆的安全性，而 Cruise 在<em>《纽约时报》</em>和其他报纸上刊登了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/kvogt/status/1679517290847694848?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1679517290847694848%7Ctwgr%5E27c05732b26210cfdd2f676a1f4b6938c8fbc5fc%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fslate.com%2Ftechnology%2F2023%2F07%2Fcruise-autonomous-vehicles-safety-waymo-self-driving-cars-ad-new-york-times.html">整版广告</a>，展示其技术作为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nhtsa.gov/press-releases/traffic-crash-death-estimates-2022#:~:text=The%20National%20Highway%20Traffic%20Safety,42%2C939%20fatalities%20reported%20for%202021.">解决</a>方案。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nhtsa.gov/press-releases/traffic-crash-death-estimates-2022#:~:text=The%20National%20Highway%20Traffic%20Safety,42%2C939%20fatalities%20reported%20for%202021.">去年美国有 42,795 人死于道路交通事故</a>。 （这些公司一直<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/cruise-waymo-want-to-keep-data-on-their-robotaxis-confidential/article_e95a1ed0-54b6-11ed-abfb-437852b227de.html">不愿</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/cruise-waymo-want-to-keep-data-on-their-robotaxis-confidential/article_e95a1ed0-54b6-11ed-abfb-437852b227de.html">分享其运营数据</a>，这妨碍了无关的研究人员客观地参与进来。）不过，目前，机器人出租车给旧金山官员带来了一系列麻烦。即使部署有限，这些车辆仍然<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://techcrunch.com/2022/06/30/cruise-robotaxis-blocked-traffic-for-hours-on-this-san-francisco-street/">堵塞了车道</a>、<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://t.co/KQlZ1y0QA8">阻碍了公共汽车和有轨电车</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/1/29/23576422/san-francisco-cruise-waymo-robotaxi-rollout">冲过消防水龙带</a>，并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://t.co/DVPVsXet8T">进入了活跃的施工区域</a>。自 2022 年 6 月以来，旧金山<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://t.co/rHiwDGEyPp">记录了近 600 起机器人出租车在公共街道上进行计划外停车的情况</a>，其中有些情况持续了几个小时。这一数字仅限于向市政府官员报告的事件，这表明实际数字可能要高得多。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/12/test-ride-waymos-self-driving-car/577378/">阅读：最后，自动驾驶汽车</a><br><br>旧金山市交通局局长杰弗里·图姆林 (Jeffrey Tumlin) 告诉我：“这些车辆在基本的郊区驾驶条件下表现非常好，但当城市更加复杂时，尤其是在遇到意外情况时，它们就会面临挑战。” “在旧金山这样的城市，意想不到的事情无处不在。”该市消防队长珍妮·尼科尔森 (Jeanine Nicholson) 对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2023-06-22/san-francisco-robotaxis-interfere-with-firetrucks-los-angeles-is-next">机器人出租车做出了直率的评价</a>：“他们还没有准备好迎接黄金时段。”加州大学伯克利分校的研究工程师 Steven Shladover 曾为加州官员提供有关自动驾驶汽车的建议，他告诉我，Cruise 和 Waymo 车辆有时会表现出令人钦佩的复杂性。但是，他说，“你几乎不可避免地会遇到这样的情况：车辆表现得像一个没有经验的驾驶员。现在还是青少年，还没有成年。”<br><br> Cruise 和 Waymo 通过宣传他们的车辆的整体安全记录来回应批评，他们认为这些记录远远优于人类驾驶员。在 CPUC 推迟放宽机器人出租车限制的决定后，Cruise <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abc7news.com/sf-self-driving-cars-robotaxis-waymo-cruise/13491184/">上个月在一份声明中宣称：</a> “我们应该尽一切可能快速、安全地扩展这项技术<em>，</em>并应对可怕的现状。” Waymo 断言：“这种拯救生命的自动驾驶技术的部署每延迟一天，都会对道路安全产生重大影响。”<br><br> Robotaxi 公司面临着快速扩张的压力。在投资了数十亿美元后，他们的支持者希望看到增长（福特和大众支持的机器人出租车著名竞争对手 Argo AI 去年的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://techcrunch.com/2022/10/26/ford-vw-backed-argo-ai-is-shutting-down/">消亡</a>，削弱了投资者对该行业的信心）。 Cruise 的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/ceo-gm-cruise-thinks-driverless-110000708.html">目标是</a>到 2030 年左右在美国街道上投放 100 万辆机器人出租车，首席执行官凯尔·沃格特 (Kyle Vogt) 在上个月的财报电话会议上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://missionlocal.org/2023/08/cruise-origin-waymo-robotaxi-driverless-car-autonomous-vehicle-california-public-utilities-commission/">表示</a>，“每个城市至少有能力容纳数千辆[机器人出租车]。” （当我通过电子邮件请求 Cruise 发表评论时，该公司没有回复我有关其扩张目标的问题。）CPUC <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cpuc.ca.gov/about-cpuc/commissioners/page-content/profile-list/commissioner-john-reynolds">（其五名成员之一</a>是 Cruise 的前任管理顾问）的任何拖延都会使公司的目标更难实现。<br><br>尽管面临当前的挑战，自动驾驶技术正在稳步改进，从公共街道上行驶的车辆收集的大量数据中推断出新的经验教训。最终，机器人出租车可能会避免困扰旧金山的交通和安全隐患。但即使机器人出租车运行完美，在机器人出租车无处不在的城市里，生活会是什么样子呢？<br><br><span class="smallcaps">在汽油动力汽车大量出现之前</span>，美国的街道上熙熙攘攘。行人、马车和自行车争先恐后地争抢空间，孩子们在人行道上玩棍球、弹球和其他游戏。有轨电车在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://americanhistory.si.edu/america-on-the-move/streetcar-city">45,000 英里的轨道</a>上运载了数百万乘客； 20 年代，芝加哥近 100 条有轨电车线路中的大多数每天 24 小时运营，其中一些在深夜<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2023-04-27/chronicling-of-the-collapse-of-public-transit-in-the-us">每隔 8 至 10 分钟</a>提供服务。 20 世纪初的城市大道<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://waterandpower.org/3%20Historic%20Photos%203/Spring_St_1902.jpg">照片</a>可能看起来很混乱，但危险有限，因为没有人行驶速度超过每小时 15 英里。<br><br>早期，除了最富裕的城市居民之外，汽车对所有人来说都太贵了。但在福特 T 型车推出后，美国汽车销量<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.richmondfed.org/publications/research/econ_focus/2003/winter/economic_history#:~:text=In%201910%2C%20the%20output%20of,to%204.5%20million%20in%201929.">猛增</a>，从 1910 年的 181,000 辆上升到 1929 年的 450 万辆。这些车辆的行驶速度比街上任何其他车辆都快，很快就对行人和儿童构成了致命威胁。 1927 年，约有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://injuryfacts.nsc.org/motor-vehicle/historical-fatality-trends/deaths-and-rates/">25,800 人</a>死于车祸，尽管当时美国人拥有的汽车少得多，但人均死亡率仍远高于今天。弗吉尼亚大学历史学家彼得·诺顿在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/fighting-traffic-the-dawn-of-the-motor-age-in-the-american-city-peter-d-norton/9780262516129?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《打击交通：美国城市汽车时代的黎明》一书中</em></a>写道：“死者都是城里人，他们没有乘坐机动车，而且还很年轻。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/car-devotion-motor-vehicle-deaths-danger/674613/">阅读：每个人都有“汽车大脑”</a><br><br>诺顿在他的书中讲述了 1920 年代初期，圣路易斯和匹兹堡的居民为车祸中丧生的人建立了巨大的纪念碑。在辛辛那提， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/figure/The-Cincinnati-speed-governor-referendum-frightened-motordom-into-organizing-to-reshape_fig1_236825193">1923 年的一项投票倡议</a>提议，要求该市内的所有机动车辆都配备调速器，速度设定为 25 英里/小时。 “仅仅在那个城市，就有四万二千人在请愿书上签名，”诺顿告诉我。 “这表明有很多人受到汽车统治的困扰。”汽车工业惊慌失措，纷纷动员起来反对辛辛那提的措施，但该措施遭到失败。<br><br>为了避免争论快速车辆是否可以与城市社区共存，汽车行业与友好的政府官员合作，将道路安全重新定义为有被撞风险的个人的责任。汽车团体资助学校<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/PeterNorton12/status/1684924437865328640?s=20">课程，</a>指导儿童不要上街，并努力将<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vox.com/2015/1/15/7551873/jaywalking-history">乱穿马路</a>定为犯罪行为。与此同时，城市<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.stltoday.com/news/archives/photos-work-in-the-20s-and-30s-widened-several-st-louis-streets/collection_7e157efb-3267-52c2-b337-733ac43205e1.html">人行道</a>和公共空间被拆除，以扩大车道。<br><br>事实证明，城市汽车对于有轨电车来说是毁灭性的，因为有轨电车无法绕过阻挡其轨道的机动车。亨特学院城市历史学家、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-great-american-transit-disaster-a-century-of-austerity-auto-centric-planning-and-white-flight-nicholas-dagen-bloom/9780226824406?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《美国交通大灾难</em></a>： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-great-american-transit-disaster-a-century-of-austerity-auto-centric-planning-and-white-flight-nicholas-dagen-bloom/9780226824406?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>一个世纪的紧缩、以汽车为中心的规划和白色飞行</em></a>，在电子邮件中告诉我。 “有轨电车缺乏专属通行权，因此爆炸性的汽车交通极大地减慢了有轨电车的服务速度。”汽车还使许多城市居民能够搬迁到交通无法到达的郊区。到 20 世纪 50 年代，美国有轨电车服务已经<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vox.com/2015/5/7/8562007/streetcar-history-demise">崩溃</a>。 1960 年，只有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://library.cqpress.com/cqresearcher/document.php?id=cqresrre1963042400">12%</a>的上班通勤是乘坐公共交通；到 2019 年，这一份额已跌至<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://t.co/zRsYNJZdEr">5%</a> 。<br><br>这些早期以汽车为中心的决策的后果至今仍在产生影响，导致城市变得更肮脏、更危险、更少乐趣。许多市中心<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vox.com/a/new-economy-future/cars-cities-technologies">一半以上</a>的土地用于移动和存放机动车辆，占用了原本可容纳住房、零售、游乐场和公园的空间。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">许多城市现在正在</span>采取措施纠正过去的错误。去年， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://denverite.com/2022/11/14/initiated-ordinance-307-results-denver-deserves-sidewalks/">丹佛</a>选民通过了一项公投，将拨款数百万美元用于改善人行道。为了使公共交通与汽车出行竞争， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yourvalley.net/stories/phoenix-plans-35th-avenue-as-first-bus-rapid-transit-route,387753">菲尼克斯</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.channel3000.com/news/local-news/madison-state-leaders-break-ground-on-city-s-bus-rapid-transit-system/article_a977a8c1-cc01-57bb-91fa-84ad374916a7.html">威斯康星州麦迪逊</a>正在规划他们的第一条快速公交线路。 （这些举措在一个世纪前就可以帮助有轨电车。）近年来，加利福尼亚州、内华达州和弗吉尼亚州已<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/losangeles/news/jaywalking-to-be-decriminalized-starting-jan-1/">采取行动</a>，将<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://americawalks.org/jaywalking-reform-progress/">乱穿马路非刑事化</a>。进步是渐进的，但却是真实的。<br><br>自动驾驶汽车威胁到了这种势头，原因很简单，自动驾驶汽车仍然是汽车。无论是由人还是软件操作，汽车都会产生污染，需要车道，并危及行人和骑自行车的人。<br><br> Safe Street Rebel 的一名成员告诉我，他同意自动驾驶汽车支持者的观点，即自动驾驶汽车可以使汽车旅行比以往任何时候都更容易——这正是问题所在（由于该组织活动的合法性令人怀疑，他要求保持匿名）。 “我们对交通的未来有两种相互竞争的愿景，”他说。 “我们现在正在讨论<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://sf.streetsblog.org/2022/11/18/spur-talk-bury-or-tear-down-us-101-and-the-central-freeway">拆除旧金山的部分高速公路</a>，但自动驾驶汽车完全反对这一点，因为它们需要道路空间才能快速行驶。如果我们有更多自动驾驶汽车，我们是否必须保留这些高速公路？或者我们可以投资改善交通，这样我们就不需要那些高速公路了？”<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/05/car-accident/618766/">约书亚·夏普：我们都应该更加害怕开车</a><br><br>弗吉尼亚大学历史学家诺顿认为这位旧金山活动人士的担忧是有道理的。 “一旦我们的街道上有了机器人出租车，那么肯定存在城市认为不必提供基本公共交通的风险，”他告诉我。事实上，这样的观点早已得到共识。 “现在不要建造轻轨系统。风投公司 Andreessen Horowitz 的合伙人 Frank Chen 在 2018 年对<em>《纽约时报》</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/20/upshot/driverless-cars-vs-transit-spending-cities.html">表示</a>：“拜托，拜托，拜托，不要。”“我们不了解自动驾驶汽车的经济原理，因为我们还没有还没有经历过它们。让我们看看结果如何。”前一年，佛罗里达州迈阿密戴德县的官员<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article152473304.html">以</a>自动驾驶汽车为理由，拒绝扩大公共交通。<br><br>但任何有关车辆本身就能显着提高机动性的说法似乎都是异想天开。几年前，研究人员为 13 名湾区志愿者提供了一名私人司机，可以带他们去任何他们想去的地方，模仿使用自动驾驶汽车的体验。在与司机在一起的一周内，测试对象的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jalopnik.com/zombie-miles-and-napa-weekends-how-a-week-with-chauffe-1839648416">行驶里程比以前多了 83%</a> 。如果自动驾驶汽车引发如此多的额外驾驶，那将是一场环境灾难。它们还可能在高速公路和街道上造成前所未有的堵塞。<br><br>伯克利研究工程师什拉多弗认为这种担忧有些言过其实。 “这取决于自动驾驶汽车的使用方式，”他说。 “如果它们以与交通互补的方式部署，例如为城市中交通便利的部分地区提供服务，那将是一个重大优势。”但营利性公司会专注于所谓的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usnews.com/news/healthiest-communities/articles/2018-04-24/transit-deserts-a-growing-problem-in-the-us">“交通荒漠”</a> ，还是会满足一小部分富裕客户的需求？为了让自动驾驶汽车补充交通线路，城市居民必须愿意与陌生人一起乘坐机器人出租车。这一<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://medium.com/cruise/sharing-a-better-future-981ca839f4a5">假设</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.autoevolution.com/news/gm-still-thinks-its-a-good-idea-to-have-strangers-ride-share-the-cruise-origin-144945.html">被内置于</a>Cruise 的小型豆荚状<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.freep.com/story/money/cars/general-motors/2023/02/25/gm-factory-zero-cruise-origin/69893597007/">Origin</a>班车中，但 Uber Pool 和 Lyft Line 的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-03-18/post-covid-ride-hail-users-may-spurn-shared-trips">麻烦</a>让人们对这个想法产生了怀疑。<br><br>即使自动驾驶汽车在技术上确实不负众望，它们对城市的长期影响也很难预测。 Cruise 发言人德鲁·普萨泰里 (Drew Pusateri) 在一封电子邮件中告诉我：“虽然有大量数据表明自动驾驶汽车可以为整体上更安全的街道做出贡献，但现实是它们存在于交通生态系统中，并不是万能药。” “我们需要采取更广泛的道路安全方法，包括对公共交通、更宽、更慢的道路和各种其他解决方案进行更多投资。”但过去的一个世纪表明，当交通系统主要是为汽车而建时，使用其他交通方式的人们就会受到冷遇。即使汽车自动驾驶，情况也可能仍然如此。<br><br>在旧金山，政府官员和活动人士正在就城市内自动驾驶汽车的可取性提出基本问题，而这些问题很少在公共场合提出。相反，在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abc13.com/connected-and-autonomous-vehicle-cav-task-force/5102433/">德克萨斯州</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/03/20/595115055/arizona-governor-helped-make-state-wild-west-for-driverless-cars">亚利桑那州</a>等州寻求创新光环的民选官员积极追求自动驾驶技术的早期部署，最大限度地减少监管并回避尖锐的问题。直到现在，在加利福尼亚州，机器人出租车公司才发现自己处于在公共领域进行防御的陌生位置。<br><br> CPUC 和其他地方的监管机构应鼓励围绕自动驾驶汽车开展充满活力的公众对话，并从中学习。他们能做的最糟糕的事情就是仓促决定扩展一项诱人的新技术，但其缺点可能是灾难性的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/robotaxis-san-francisco-self-driven-car/674956/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/robotaxis-san-francisco-self-driven-car/674956/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[I Was Wrong About Trigger Warnings]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>全国对创伤的痴迷是否对少女造成了真正的伤害？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/USCD1PWDIZqx73rQbaHcE6W5flY=/106x0:2026x2400/648x810/media/img/2023/07/31/DIS_Filipovic_TriggerWarnings/original.jpg" alt="一本由玻璃制成、在绿色背景上破碎的黑白学生作文书的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>丹妮尔·德尔·柏拉图插图</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">2008 年</span>，当我还是女性博客的撰稿人时，评论者开始要求在讨论令人痛苦的话题（最常见的是性侵犯）的帖子顶部发出警告。不幸的是，暴力不可避免地成为女权主义写作的核心。强奸、家庭暴力、种族主义暴力、厌女症——这些事件不可磨灭地塑造着女性的生活，无论我们是直接经历这些事件，还是因害怕它们而调整自己的行为。<br><br>当时，我确信这样的警告有时是必要的，以传达当前主题的严重性（ <i>“严重问题”</i>这个词在我的署名下出现了很多次）。即便如此，我还是对添加更多触发警告的要求感到恼火，尤其是当标题已经明确了帖子的内容时。但警告正在成为在线女权主义空间的常态，帖子顶部的四个字——“触发警告：性侵犯”——似乎是为了我们社区的福祉而做出的一个简单的妥协。我们以为我们正在让世界变得更美好一点。直到很久以后我才意识到我们可能是问题的一部分。<br><br>警告很快就成倍增加。当我写道一项保守派立法“太糟糕了，让我想呕吐”时，一位评论者要求发出饮食失调触发警告。当我发布一个有趣的<em>BuzzFeed</em>照片合集的链接时，一位评论者说它需要触发警告，因为猫攻击狗的照片看起来像家庭暴力。有时我会翻白眼；有时我会回应，告诉人们要抓紧。尽管如此，我告诉自己，总的原则是一个很好的原则——在展示可能让人们不安的材料之前警告他们。<br><br>触发警告从女权主义网站和博客转移到大学校园和进步团体。通常，他们似乎更多地强调某些话题的令人不安的本质，而不是照顾经历过创伤事件的人。到 2013 年，它们变得如此普遍，也如此富有争议，以至于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/human-interest/2013/12/trigger-warnings-from-the-feminist-blogosphere-to-shonda-rhimes-in-2013.html"><em>Slate</em>宣布今年</a>为“触发警告之年”。<br><br>问题从此变得更加复杂。 2016 年左右，在康奈尔大学负责学生心理健康项目 22 年的理查德·弗里德曼 (Richard Friedman) 开始发现寻求帮助的人数每年增加 10% 或 15%。 “不仅如此，”他告诉我，“年轻人谈论令人不安的事件的方式也发生了变化。”他描述了“这种被不熟悉和不舒服的事物伤害的感觉。相对于可能造成的实际伤害，所使用的语言似乎有些夸大。我的意思是，我很惊讶——人们对我们从未想过会危险的事情感到<i>非常</i>不安。”例如，一些学生抱怨讲师发表了他们不喜欢的评论，或者老师的信仰与他们的个人价值观相矛盾。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2019/03/do-trigger-warnings-work/585871/">阅读：触发警告的真正问题</a><br><br>弗里德曼说，在某种程度上，这代表了积极的变化。精神疾病比以往任何时候都不再受到污名化，寻求治疗也更加普遍。但弗里德曼担心学生们也认为自己很脆弱，并且似乎认为接触冒犯性或挑战性的信息对心理上有害。在要求对可能令人不安的课堂材料发出更强有力的警告时，学生们似乎在说：<i>这可能会伤害我们，而这个机构应该保护我们免受痛苦。</i><br><br>我们是否无意中培养了一代人，他们应对困难的工具较少？<br><br>触发警告只是更大转变的一部分。投诉很快就进入了更广泛的文化，并被应用于“有毒”的工作场所和“有问题的”同事；学生们谴责思想造成的“潜在创伤”，并反对一些演讲者和艺术作品的出现。<br><br>讽刺的是，我自己对这一切的怀疑来自于对创伤的报道。我采访过世界各地的女性，了解人类对彼此所做的最糟糕的事情。我开始注意到研究人员对创伤和复原力的理解与进步机构运用这些概念的方式之间存在令人担忧的不一致。我开始质疑自己在这一切中扮演的角色。<br><br>女权主义作家试图让我们的互联网小角落变得更加温和，同时也对那些被推入阴影的极其普遍的女性经历给予适当的认可。在某种程度上，这些努力起了作用。但随着<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/02/the-tragic-mystery-of-teenage-anxiety/673076/">青春期女孩和大学生的心理健康</a>崩溃，以及包括女权主义组织在内的激进组织发现自己一再卷入有关权力和语言的自相残杀的争论，一个问题困扰着我们：在更加重视个人伤害和受害的主张时，我们是否无意中培养了一代人，他们管理困难和将逆境转化为能动性的工具较少？<br><br><span class="smallcaps">自从我</span>成为女权主义博主以来，青少年的心理健康状况直线下降。从2007年到2019年，10岁到14岁儿童的自杀率增加了两倍；对于该年龄段的女孩来说，这一比例几乎翻了两番。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/data/yrbs/pdf/YRBS_Data-Summary-Trends_Report2023_508.pdf">CDC 2021 年的一份报告发现</a>，57% 的女高中生表示“持续感到悲伤或绝望”，而 2011 年这一比例为 36%。尽管这场流行病无疑导致了青少年心理健康的崩溃，但这种衰退早在新冠疫情爆发之前就开始了。打。<br><br>十几岁的女孩报告说，性暴力和欺凌的发生率高得令人不安，她们也担心自己在学校的人身安全。但目前尚不清楚他们的物质条件是否急剧下降，足以解释他们的心理健康状况下降。疾病预防控制中心的研究表明，在过去十年中，高中生中的欺凌行为实际上在某些方面有所减少。与十年前相比，如今的青少年饮酒或使用非法药物的可能性也有所降低。甚至在流行病救助资金大幅降低儿童贫困率之前， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/library/stories/2022/09/record-drop-in-child-poverty.html">2012年之后生活在贫困中的儿童比例就急剧下降</a>。美国公立高中生毕业的可能性比我国历史上任何时候都高，而且女孩毕业的可能性明显高于男孩。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/11/facebooks-dangerous-experiment-teen-girls/620767/">乔纳森·海特：针对少女的危险实验</a><br><br>那么自 2010 年左右以来，少女的情况发生了哪些恶化呢？心理健康状况恶化背后的因素是不透明且复杂的，但一个重大变化是青少年与朋友面对面相处的时间减少，每周减少 11 个小时——这一下降趋势在大流行之前就开始了，但后来急剧恶化通过它。自 2014 年以来，拥有智能手机的青少年比例上升了 22%，而自称“几乎经常”使用互联网的比例<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/internet/2022/08/10/teens-social-media-and-technology-2022/">也增加了一倍</a>。部分问题可能在于社交媒体生态系统，它让青少年生活在志同道合的同龄人的泡沫中，并倾向于优先考虑最响亮、最愤愤不平的声音；这种孤立可以鼓励青少年将痛苦的经历理解为创伤。 “我认为他们更容易人为地营造舒适的环境，”医生兼创伤后应激障碍 (PTSD) 专家 Shaili Jain 告诉我。 “我认为这适得其反。因为当他们处于不舒服的境地时，他们会感到非常震惊。”<br><br>将创伤语言应用于事件会改变我们处理事件的方式。这可能是一件好事，让一个人面对一个真正将他们的生活分为前后的时刻，并寻求帮助并开始治愈。或者它可能会放大无助和绝望的感觉，使这些感觉超越能力和控制感。<br><br> “心理健康界有这样一句话：‘感知就是现实’，”杰恩说。 “因此，如果有人坚持认为他们感到某些事情造成了创伤，那就是他们的现实，这可能会对心理健康产生影响。”<br><br>宾夕法尼亚大学积极心理学中心主任马丁·塞利格曼 (Martin Seligman) 在过去 50 年里一直在研究复原力。他与人合着的一项研究着眼于美国陆军，看看是否有办法预测创伤后应激障碍。毫不奇怪，他和他的研究同事发现了与士兵所经历的战斗的严重程度之间的联系。但士兵们在战场上所经历的预先存在的性格也很重要。 “如果你是一个灾难制造者，在最糟糕的 10% 或 20% 中，当你面临严峻的战斗时，你患 PTSD 的可能性是三倍多，”塞利格曼告诉我。 “在每一个严重程度的战斗中都是如此——百分比有所下降，但即使是温和的战斗或没有明显的战斗，它仍然大约是两倍高。”<br><br>换句话说，一个人认为自己能够坚持克服困难或无法应对困难的感觉可以是自我实现的。塞利格曼告诉我：“当我们克服并应对生活中的逆境和创伤时，我们就会变得更加精通、更加适应、更加有能力抵御未来的糟糕事件。” “但相反，我们有一种意识形态或信念，认为当创伤事件发生时，我们是无助的受害者——这种意识形态或信念会自食其果。”<br><br>塞利格曼还发现，一些经历过严重创伤的士兵不仅能够活下来，而且实际上将痛苦转化为力量的源泉。 “大约有同样多的患有创伤后应激障碍的人表现出一种叫做创伤后成长的东西，这意味着他们在事件中度过了一段糟糕的时光，但一年后，他们的身体和心理都比开始时更强大，”他说。但这种赋予权力的信息尚未在社会中扎根。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">那么，什么是</span>应对逆境更有效的方法呢？康奈尔大学前心理健康协调员弗里德曼将增强复原力与体育锻炼进行了比较。 “这就像任何形式的力量训练，”他告诉我。 “人们会毫不犹豫地去健身房，并忍受肌肉疼痛，以变得更强壮，并看起来像他们想要的样子。第二天他们醒来时会说，‘天啊，这太痛苦了。我好痛。那不是创伤性的。然而，当你把它带入情感世界时，它突然变得非常不利。”<br><br>问题在于，这种想法——为了培养韧性，我们必须克服困难——给某些人带来了比其他人更重的负担。弗里德曼指出，在持续压力下长大的人（可能是由于虐待、贫困或粮食不安全）可能会发现这种压力“侵蚀”了他们使用弹性肌肉的能力。锻炼的比喻激怒了加拿大哈利法克斯达尔豪斯大学弹性研究中心主任迈克尔·昂加尔(Michael Ungar)。 “长期暴露在种族主义、厌女症、不断受到侮辱或排斥、体能歧视等压力源下——所有这些因素确实会让我们疲惫不堪；它们让我们更容易受到难以承受的情绪的影响，”他告诉我。毕竟，当一个人感觉周围的每个人都在告诉他们相反的时候，只有那么多次，一个人才能说服自己，他们可以坚持下去。<br><br>创造有弹性的条件既是个人的责任，也是集体的责任。<br><br>蒂法尼·蒙福德·登特 (Tyffani Monford Dent) 是一位临床心理学家，也是一位专注于性暴力和种族创伤的作家，她将此称为“弹性陷阱”。她告诉我，尤其是黑人女性，长期以来因其坚韧和毅力而受到赞扬，但个人的韧性无法解决结构性问题。从登特的角度来看，年轻人并不拒绝内在力量的概念；他们只是拒绝内在力量的概念。他们拒绝仅靠个人毅力应对系统性不公正的要求。当他们谈论伤害和创伤时，他们并没有表现出软弱；而是表现出软弱。他们说，<i>是的，我很脆弱，这就是人性</i>。如今，患者“对于自己需要什么才能感到舒适、感到安全、感到在这个世界上受到重视”变得更加透明，她说。 “那是一件坏事？”<br><br>我采访过的大多数专家都小心翼翼地区分了学生向教授寻求特定住宿以帮助他们处理过去创伤的个别学生，以及完全避免挑战或令人不安的情况的文化倾向。蓬勃发展需要克服不适和困难。但创造能够实现这种韧性的条件既是个人的责任，也是集体的责任。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">如果我们想</span>用韧性文化取代创伤文化，我们就必须重新学习如何互相支持——随着我们的社会逐渐将“健康”视为一种个人追求、一种状态，我们已经失去了这种支持。通过自我工作进入心灵。向内退缩，将我们的身份与所有受到伤害的方式联系起来，实际上可能会让我们的内心世界变得更难居住。<br><br> “如果一切都是创伤性的，而我们没有能力应对这些时刻，那么当更极端的事情发生时，我们的应对能力又如何呢？”昂加尔说道。 “韧性在一定程度上是为下一个压力源准备资源。”这些资源必须是内部和外部的。如果我们想要改善福祉，社会变革是必要的，但只有当我们的运动由那些相信自己所面临的逆境是可以克服的、不公正不一定是永久性的、世界可以变得更好，并且他们有能力做出这种改变。<br><br>为了帮助人们增强抵御能力，我们需要提供物质援助来满足基本需求。我们需要修复破裂的社区关系，让我们中更少的人感到自己在独自挣扎。我们需要鼓励培养超越自我的使命感。我们也知道什么阻碍了恢复力：避免困难的想法和不完美的人，灾难性的，孤立自己的头脑。<br><br>在采访经历过性暴力的女性时，我尽量不把创伤事件置于我们谈话的中心。相反，我的目标是尽可能多地了解他们作为人——他们的家庭、他们的工作、他们的兴趣、什么让他们快乐，以及他们在哪里最能感受到自己。我总是在谈话结束时要求他们反思自己已经走了多远，以及他们最自豪的是什么。<br><br>最后一个问题常常会引起强烈的回应。我开始问这个问题是因为我希望让我遇到的女性感受到被完整地看待，超越发生在她们身上的最糟糕的事情。<br><br><small><em>本文发表于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/toc/2023/09">2023 年 9 月</a>印刷版，标题为“弹性差距”。</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/trigger-warnings-feminism-teen-girls-mental-health/674759/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/trigger-warnings-feminism-teen-girls-mental-health/674759/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[I’m Supporting Colombia Now]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>就其电动风格以及其球员为进入女足世界杯所克服的一切而言，这是理所当然的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/TWooRl9bCWX25OvfVb8kHplYDyE=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/fifa_world_cup/original.jpg" alt="哥伦比亚的琳达·凯塞多和四名牙买加球员一起参加了女足世界杯的比赛" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Asanka Brendon Ratnayake / 路透社</figcaption></figure>宿命论可能是粉丝最好的朋友。当美国女队开始本届世界杯时，我希望最好的事情发生，但我的大脑不断警告我，这支球队注定会遇到最坏的情况。令人痛苦的是，球队没有得到很好的训练，关键球员的受伤导致球队无法克服糟糕的战术。从第一场比赛开始，我观看了比赛的其余部分，寻找另一个国家，如果美国队熄火的话，我可以采用这个国家作为我自己的国家。<br><br>西班牙以其复杂的传球和时尚的控球能力引起了我的注意。作为一名亲英人士，我对英格兰队很感兴趣，直到英格兰球星劳伦·詹姆斯（Lauren James） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foxnews.com/sports/england-star-lauren-james-gets-red-card-violent-conduct-egregious-act-nigeria">鲁莽地</a>将球鞋插入倒地的尼日利亚球员米歇尔·阿洛齐（Michelle Alozie）的背部，而英格兰队则急忙缓和了进攻。但现在美国队已经退出世界杯，每个中立的善意球迷都应该热烈支持这个国家，因为它的电动风格和球员们努力克服的一切。那支球队是哥伦比亚。<br><br>尽管人们很容易赞扬<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/womens-world-cup-2023-nwsl-megan-rapinoe-alyssa-thompson/674816/">女子运动的进步</a>以及美国女性在争取同工同酬方面取得的成功，但许多国家仍然以令人震惊的方式对待她们的女运动员。哥伦比亚可以说是记录在案的最令人震惊的例子。<br><br>由于该国中场球员丹妮拉·蒙托亚的勇敢，我们对此了解很多。 2015年女足世界杯期间，她的球队晋级16强，这对于刚刚起步的哥伦比亚女足来说是一项令人难以置信的成就。她的队友不仅没有获得同工同酬，而且还未能获得同等报酬。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">据报道，他们根本没有得到</a>任何报酬，只是得到一点费用帮助。当蒙托亚向媒体抱怨时，她的国家足协拒绝了她参加 2016 年夏季奥运会的名单。后来，她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-usa-colombia/women-footballers-in-colombia-revolt-over-mistreatment-idUSKBN1QQ0F1">挥舞着</a>一名哥伦比亚足球官员的音频片段，据称解释说她因鲁莽开口而受到惩罚。<br><br>这种工资盗窃现象在哥伦比亚比赛中十分猖獗。一支女子球队，Atlético Huila，赢得了南美大陆俱乐部冠军——解放者杯。球员们被告知，他们的胜利将总共获得约 55,000 美元的奖金。但球队的奖金<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">显然被支付</a>给了一位为球队提供资金的商人。和蒙托亚一样，向媒体提出这些抱怨的球员也被排除在国家队名单之外，尽管她所施加的压力迫使俱乐部最终给了这些女性承诺的奖励。<br><br>这些事件只会增加官方的一系列不尊重行为：球员们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://assembly.malala.org/stories/colombian-womens-soccer">抱怨</a>国家足协让他们支付自己的国际航班费用，甚至不给他们买新<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-usa-colombia/women-footballers-in-colombia-revolt-over-mistreatment-idUSKBN1QQ0F1">球衣</a>。哥伦比亚俱乐部的一位有权有势的老板，同时也是该国参议院的成员，曾将女子比赛<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://as.com/futbol/2018/12/20/internacional/1545338936_774939.html">描述</a>为“女同性恋的培养皿”。<br><br>情况变得更糟。代表哥伦比亚参加国际青年锦标赛的 U-17 国家队技术总监据称虐待队内的女孩。根据 2019 年提出的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://colombiareports.com/amp/womens-football-in-colombia-harassment-blackmail-and-sexual-assault-of-minors/">指控</a>，他对这些青少年进行了不当触摸、向他们求爱，并未经他们同意进入他们的酒店房间。 （亚利桑那州立大学的一个项目“全球体育事务”在一份出色的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">报告</a>中对此进行了叙述。）再次，发声的球员被排除在国家队之外。技术总监同意认罪交易，承认减少了指控，但逃脱了牢狱之灾。<br><br>尽管如此，在今年的世界杯上，哥伦比亚女足当之无愧地击败了世界排名第二的德国队。他们刚刚淘汰了牙买加队，晋级四分之一决赛，周六他们将对阵实力耗尽的英格兰队。<br><br>哥伦比亚队令人兴奋的核心是 18 岁的攻击手琳达·凯塞多 (Linda Caicedo)，她是本届锦标赛的亮点，现在经常被誉为有潜力成为足球史上最伟大的球员之一。她可以运球击败一大群防守者，也可以用突破线的传球撕开防守。 （她对德国队的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5KdC3RiEnY4">进球</a>展现了无可挑剔的步法，是迄今为止比赛中最好的进球之一。）<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-national-team-soccer-world-cup/674885/">阅读：美国女足统治地位的终结</a><br><br>即使她没有那么才华横溢，单凭她的传记就足以令人着迷。 15岁时，她被诊断出患有卵巢癌，需要手术。尽管身患疾病且年事已高，她仍继续<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/08/02/1191392108/colombia-linda-caicedo-world-cup">批评</a>她的雇主哥伦比亚足协对待球队的恶劣态度。她的技术显然非常出色，以至于西班牙超级俱乐部皇家马德里将她转移到了迅速进步的女足球队中。尽管如此，从凯塞多的病史来看，她的脆弱感始终存在。上周，在哥伦比亚队与德国队的比赛之前，一段视频拍摄到她在训练中突然倒地，脸朝下躺在草地上，医护人员赶来救她。团队的官方解释是疲劳，但这一集抓住了崇高的完美和偶然性的结合，使凯塞多成为一个令人同情且最终不可抗拒的主角。<br><br>哥伦比亚队的表现最令人兴奋的也许是它与球迷的联系。前往澳大利亚和新西兰的哥伦比亚队伍是本届赛事规模最大、声音最大的队伍之一。这本身就是一项成就：尽管她们在途中遇到了业主和官员的阻挠，但妇女们还是成功地赢得了她们的同胞的支持。从某种意义上说，这使她们成为美国女性的真正继承人，她们在巅峰时期也凭借勇敢的行动主义和球场上的卓越表现改变了公众舆论。美国人，拥抱哥伦比亚队就像拥抱自己的球队一样。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:22:38 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-world-cup-colombia/674958/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-world-cup-colombia/674958/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Welcome to the Age of ‘Foomscrolling’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> LK-99 和 ChatGPT 引发的网络狂热揭示了技术乐观主义的复苏，以及对新技术的共同渴望，这种新技术将使我们摆脱人类的限制。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/yP3vUxT9CICFGM-CAF-gr3x3Fo4=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/lk_99_foomscroll_/original.jpg" alt="许多手机的插图，每部手机都显示一个漂浮的“LK99”肿块的图像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>我记得第一次看到漂浮的岩石时的情景。那是半夜，我面临着失眠者的困境：要不要去拿电话。我到达并打开了 Twitter——那是两周前的事了； <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-x-rebrand-juvenile-internet-style/674875/">新名字</a>还没有被人们所接受——理论上来说，滚动浏览我的提要可能会达到某种催眠效果，为睡眠创造一个机会。就在那时我看到了模糊的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://sciencecast.org/casts/suc384jly50n">视频</a>。其中，一块小而畸形的材料碎片，像铅笔折断的铅尖一样，神秘地悬浮在厚厚的抛光金属晶片上方。<br><br>我直接滚动过去。尽管关注了相当多的“纯粹的科学事物”聚合器，但在凌晨时分，我并不总是对启发感到兴奋。但几分钟后，我又看到了这个视频，然后是第三次。我注意到这不是对磁力的说教解释。这是新闻：漂浮的岩石是 LK-99，一种由韩国科学家团队合成的物质，他们认为它是一种室温环境压力超导体。<br><br>我想告诉大家，那天晚上<em>“室温常压超导体”</em>这个词对我来说很有意义，但没有。我对这句话感到困惑，就像猿猴审视着一块巨石。我寻找上下文线索。我数了数感叹号。经过几分钟的内心抵制后，我做了一些尽职调查，我的意思是轻松而睡眼惺忪地谷歌搜索。最终，通过一些努力，我了解到 LK-99 可能是材料科学家的圣杯发现。<br><br>但不仅仅是材料科学家！这与 2020 年在金星大气层中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2020/09/venus-life-phosphine-microbes/616342/">观测</a>到的磷化氢不同。如果这一发现成立（可惜<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/content/article/potential-signs-life-venus-are-fading-astronomers-downgrade-their-original-claims">事实并非如此</a>），它将强烈表明该行星上存在生命，这是一项划时代的发现，但不会改变我们的世界。室温超导体的存在不仅仅是一个关于自然的新事实。相反，根据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theconversation.com/room-temperature-superconductors-could-revolutionize-electronics-an-electrical-engineer-explains-the-materials-potential-201849">一些</a>观察家的说法，这意味着我们可以获得一种神奇的、万能的物质，它可以将我们带入一个新技术时代，电力在我们的世界中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theconversation.com/how-do-superconductors-work-a-physicist-explains-what-it-means-to-have-resistance-free-electricity-202308">毫无摩擦地</a>流动，更多的计算机是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thequantuminsider.com/2023/08/03/how-would-room-temperature-superconductors-change-quantum-computing/">量子的</a>，火车也是如此，很<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-02481-0">飘逸</a>。<br><br>鉴于 LK-99 据称是进口的，一场<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/lk99-superconductors-floating-rocks/674939/">复制韩国研究结果的</a>全球竞赛已经开始，互联网上的许多人都兴奋地观看着。中国首先到达那里的幽灵增添了一层地缘政治阴谋。 （我喜欢想象美国的材料科学家挤在一起，准备迎接他们的人造卫星时刻。） 与此同时， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/23820077/lk-99-superconductor-experts">据报道</a>韩国科学家之间也存在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newscientist.com/article/2384782-room-temperature-superconductor-breakthrough-met-with-scepticism/?utm_source=rakuten&amp;utm_medium=affiliate&amp;utm_campaign=2116208:Skimlinks.com&amp;utm_content=10&amp;ranMID=47192&amp;ranEAID=TnL5HPStwNw&amp;ranSiteID=TnL5HPStwNw-w0iN0psrMFqpajHAWVaDMA">争执</a>。每个人都可以在社交媒体上关注，惊叹于每块悬浮的岩石，就像 Twitch 观众惊叹于游戏玩家最新的击杀镜头一样。如果不出意外的话，这是一种打发时间的好方法，直到一个闪闪发光的科技乌托邦在我们周围实现。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/lk99-superconductors-floating-rocks/674939/">阅读：浮石的重要一周</a><br><br>明确地说，我所描述的是我所经历过的 LK-99 周围的氛围。最接近的类似可能是去年 11 月 ChatGPT 发布时的狂热。也许您还记得：大流行晚期的不适正在逐渐消退；人们已经准备好接受闪亮的新事物；然后，突然间，这些东西以机器人的形式出现，它们可以聊天、编码，甚至可能破坏你的婚姻。社交媒体上充斥着他们最聪明、最狡猾的攻击行为的屏幕截图<em>。</em><br><br>在 ChatGPT 发布后的几个月里，一些人开始相信正在发生“<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/foom">爆炸</a>”。在人工智能文献中，当人工智能的级联自我改进加速其自身发展，直至其变得强大到超出人类理解范围时，就会出现繁荣。 （这个词的意思是让人想起爆炸性喷发的声音。）这种特殊的、所谓的爆炸的巧妙之处在于：它是实时体验的，至少对于那些足够在线的人来说是这样。我们被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://a16z.com/2023/06/06/ai-will-save-the-world/">告知，</a>技术即将让我们摆脱痛苦和匮乏，你可以在 Twitter 上看到这一切。在特朗普担任总统期间，创造了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/doomscrolling-the-new-high-tech-way-to-slide-into-despair-11607640701"><em>“doomscrolling”</em></a>这个词来描述通过智能手机发布坏消息的习惯。这是不同的；它具有正价。称之为 fooscrolling。<br><br>并非所有新兴技术都会导致 fooscrolling。当它的非凡力量可以通过一些立即可识别的视觉形式（例如双音聊天屏幕截图或漂浮的岩石）来展示时，这种行为就更有可能发生。更重要的是，要获得 Foomscrolling 的资格，新兴技术必须是能够合理提升物种水平的技术。 （阿波罗任务会导致无休止的滚动；想象一下，<em>地出</em>照片有 100 万次转发，<span class="smallcaps">标题是我们回来了</span>。）GLP-1 受体激活药物，比如 Ozempic 中的药物，提供了一个有启发性的反例。尽管构成了人们期待已久的奇迹——一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.statnews.com/2023/08/08/novo-nordisk-wegovy-cardiovascular-risk/">有效</a>的减肥药——但它们只能解决某些问题<em>。</em>没有人发帖称这些药物最终将解决气候变化问题； Ozempic 不会提示任何人进行 fooscroll。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/06/ozempic-pills-obesity-drugs-semaglutide/674541/">阅读：再见，臭氧</a><br><br>就人工智能而言，快速滚动很快就变成了一种自嘲的东西：人工智能影响者的家庭手工业。他们支付了蓝色支票和个人简历，小心翼翼地洗白了他们之前对加密货币的热情。最初，它们很有用。该领域发展迅速，有一些行业新闻聚合器是件好事，尽管有些人容易轻信。但他们很快就声称本周令人心碎的突破清单比上周更广泛，从而压倒了讨论。这一切开始显得有点悲伤，就像 LinkedIn 一样。<br><br>也许这只是 fooscrolling 循环。最近几天，LK-99 粉丝群体一直处于不利地位。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-08-08/superconductor-lk-99-sample-may-be-available-in-weeks">通货紧缩现实主义</a>的光环已经开始为这个故事增添色彩。一些评论家声称 LK-99 只是一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/alexkaplan0/status/1688734992682086400">铁磁体</a>，科学家们已经得到消息，即使这种物质确实是室温超导体，通往<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/the-world-if">“社会将如何看待”模因</a>中描绘的未来之路也将是漫长的。一。复制声明不再是我的“为你”提要的首要内容。细微差别和清醒似乎赢得了胜利。<br><br>超导滚动的顶峰可能已经过去了。但推动它的文化欲望——对一种新工具的渴望，能够帮助我们摆脱人性的弱点，走上某种平稳的指数轨迹，通向闪闪发光和不朽的未来——看起来相当有弹性。这种集体渴望可能从奥杜瓦伊以来就以这样或那样的形式伴随着我们。互联网只是将其放大为一种探照灯。我想象它的光束很快就会找到其他东西来锁定，世界上的失眠症患者可以在夜深人静的时候用谷歌搜索一些新的东西，希望这一次，繁荣将是真实的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 20:47:40 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/foomscrolling-ai-chatgpt-lk-99-superconductor/674955/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/foomscrolling-ai-chatgpt-lk-99-superconductor/674955/</item></channel></rss>